{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_012cnXnfFkNTrpV8WkpMkBAP","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→/-\n     2→Copyright (c) 2026 Elman Project. All rights reserved.\n     3→Released under Apache 2.0 license.\n     4→Authors: Elman Project Contributors\n     5→-/\n     6→import Mathlib.LinearAlgebra.Matrix.NonsingularInverse\n     7→import Mathlib.Data.Matrix.Basic\n     8→import Mathlib.Analysis.Normed.Group.Basic\n     9→import Mathlib.Analysis.SpecialFunctions.Trigonometric.Basic\n    10→import Mathlib.Analysis.SpecialFunctions.ExpDeriv\n    11→import Mathlib.Topology.Basic\n    12→import ElmanProofs.Expressivity.E1HDefinition\n    13→\n    14→/-!\n    15→# E88 Matrix State Strictly Exceeds E1H Vector State\n    16→\n    17→This file proves the capacity separation between E88 and E1H architectures:\n    18→- E88 head state is a D×D matrix with D² scalar entries per head\n    19→- E1H head state is a D-vector with D scalar entries per head\n    20→- For D ≥ 2: D² > D, so E88 has strictly more state capacity per head\n    21→\n    22→## Connection to Empirical Results\n    23→\n    24→E88 achieves 1.19 perplexity at 32K vs E1H's 1.10. The D-fold state capacity\n    25→increase enables E88 to maintain richer associative memories and longer-range\n    26→dependencies across the sequence.\n    27→\n    28→## Main Theorems\n    29→\n    30→* `e88_capacity_d_squared` - E88 matrix state has D² degrees of freedom\n    31→* `e1h_capacity_d` - E1H vector state has D degrees of freedom\n    32→* `e88_addressable_e1h_not` - E88 supports S·q content-based retrieval; E1H cannot\n    33→* `capacity_separation` - For D ≥ 2, E88 state scalars > E1H state scalars\n    34→\n    35→## Proof Strategy\n    36→\n    37→1. **Counting argument**: The index set for E88 state entries is `Fin D × Fin D`\n    38→   (cardinality D²), while for E1H it is `Fin D` (cardinality D). For D ≥ 2, D² > D.\n    39→\n    40→2. **Addressability**: E88's matrix state S allows content-addressable retrieval\n    41→   via S · q (matrix-vector product). We demonstrate concretely:\n    42→   - Store S = e₀ ⊗ e₀ᵀ (outer product of first basis vector)\n    43→   - Query with e₀ (first basis): retrieves e₀ (nonzero)\n    44→   - Query with e₁ (second basis, orthogonal): retrieves 0\n    45→   - Different queries → different results → content-addressable\n    46→\n    47→3. **Separation**: Uses the already-proven `E1H.e88_state_exceeds_e1h_state`\n    48→   which shows D < D² for D ≥ 2 (proven in E1HDefinition.lean).\n    49→\n    50→-/\n    51→\n    52→namespace CapacitySeparation\n    53→\n    54→open Real Matrix Finset BigOperators\n    55→\n    56→/-! ## Part 1: Degrees of Freedom Counting -/\n    57→\n    58→/-- **THEOREM 1: E88 matrix state has D² degrees of freedom**\n    59→\n    60→Each E88 head state is a D×D matrix. The index set for its entries is\n    61→`Fin D × Fin D`, which has cardinality D * D = D².\n    62→\n    63→This quantifies the number of independent real parameters stored per E88 head. -/\n    64→theorem e88_capacity_d_squared (d : ℕ) :\n    65→    Fintype.card (Fin d × Fin d) = d * d := by\n    66→  simp [Fintype.card_prod, Fintype.card_fin]\n    67→\n    68→/-- **THEOREM 2: E1H vector state has D degrees of freedom**\n    69→\n    70→Each E1H head state is a D-dimensional vector. The index set is `Fin D`,\n    71→which has cardinality D.\n    72→\n    73→This quantifies the number of independent real parameters stored per E1H head. -/\n    74→theorem e1h_capacity_d (d : ℕ) :\n    75→    Fintype.card (Fin d) = d := Fintype.card_fin d\n    76→\n    77→/-- For D ≥ 2, E88 has strictly more degrees of freedom than E1H:\n    78→    D < D² (equivalently, D < D * D when D ≥ 2) -/\n    79→theorem e88_dof_strictly_exceeds_e1h (d : ℕ) (hd : d ≥ 2) :\n    80→    Fintype.card (Fin d) < Fintype.card (Fin d × Fin d) := by\n    81→  simp [Fintype.card_prod, Fintype.card_fin]\n    82→  nlinarith\n    83→\n    84→/-! ## Part 2: Content-Addressable Retrieval -/\n    85→\n    86→/-- E88 content-addressable read: compute S · q\n    87→\n    88→E88's state S (a D×D matrix) can be \"queried\" with a vector q by computing\n    89→the matrix-vector product S · q. This is the fundamental retrieval mechanism:\n    90→- If S accumulated outer products v_k ⊗ k^T for key-value pairs (k, v_k),\n    91→  then S · q selects values weighted by key-query similarity. -/\n    92→noncomputable def e88ContentRead {d : ℕ} (S : Matrix (Fin d) (Fin d) ℝ)\n    93→    (q : Fin d → ℝ) : Fin d → ℝ :=\n    94→  S.mulVec q\n    95→\n    96→/-- Helper: inner product of orthogonal basis vectors is 0.\n    97→For the standard basis vectors e₀ (= 1 at index 0, 0 elsewhere) and\n    98→e₁ (= 1 at index 1, 0 elsewhere), their inner product is 0. -/\n    99→private theorem basis_inner_product_zero (d : ℕ) :\n   100→    ∑ j : Fin d, (if j.val = 0 then (1:ℝ) else 0) * (if j.val = 1 then 1 else 0) = 0 := by\n   101→  apply Finset.sum_eq_zero\n   102→  intro j _\n   103→  split_ifs with h0 h1\n   104→  · -- j.val = 0 and j.val = 1: impossible\n   105→    exact absurd (h0.symm.trans h1) (by decide)\n   106→  · ring\n   107→  · ring\n   108→  · ring\n   109→\n   110→/-- Helper: inner product of e₀ with itself is 1. -/\n   111→private theorem basis_self_inner_product (d : ℕ) (hd0 : 0 < d) :\n   112→    ∑ j : Fin d, (if j.val = 0 then (1:ℝ) else 0) * (if j.val = 0 then 1 else 0) = 1 := by\n   113→  -- Simplify (if p then 1 else 0) * (if p then 1 else 0) = if p then 1 else 0\n   114→  have h_sq : ∀ j : Fin d, (if j.val = 0 then (1:ℝ) else 0) * (if j.val = 0 then 1 else 0) =\n   115→                             if j.val = 0 then 1 else 0 := fun j => by split_ifs <;> ring\n   116→  simp_rw [h_sq]\n   117→  -- Convert j.val = 0 condition to j = ⟨0, hd0⟩ for Fin d\n   118→  have h_conv : ∀ j : Fin d, (if j.val = 0 then (1:ℝ) else 0) = if j = ⟨0, hd0⟩ then 1 else 0 :=\n   119→    fun j => by simp [Fin.ext_iff]\n   120→  simp_rw [h_conv]\n   121→  -- Apply sum_ite_eq: ∑ j in univ, if j = a then f j else 0 = if a ∈ univ then f a else 0\n   122→  simp\n   123→\n   124→/-- **THEOREM 3: E88 supports S·q content-based retrieval that E1H cannot**\n   125→\n   126→We formally demonstrate E88's content-addressable retrieval by constructing:\n   127→- A state S = e₀ ⊗ e₀ᵀ (outer product of the first standard basis vector)\n   128→- Two queries e₀ ≠ e₁ (orthogonal basis vectors)\n   129→- S · e₀ = e₀ (nonzero: retrieves the stored association)\n   130→- S · e₁ = 0   (zero: orthogonal query finds nothing)\n   131→\n   132→So different queries retrieve different information from the same state.\n   133→\n   134→**Why E1H cannot do this**: E1H's state is a D-vector h, not a matrix.\n   135→Any \"read\" operation on h produces the same information (or a fixed linear\n   136→projection thereof) regardless of any \"query\" vector — there is no matrix\n   137→to multiply against, so no key-based addressing is possible.\n   138→\n   139→This difference explains why E88 can implement associative memory patterns\n   140→(key-value retrieval) that E1H fundamentally cannot. -/\n   141→theorem e88_addressable_e1h_not (d : ℕ) (hd : d ≥ 2) :\n   142→    ∃ (S : Matrix (Fin d) (Fin d) ℝ) (q₁ q₂ : Fin d → ℝ),\n   143→      q₁ ≠ q₂ ∧ e88ContentRead S q₁ ≠ e88ContentRead S q₂ := by\n   144→  have hd0 : 0 < d := by omega\n   145→  have hd1 : 1 < d := by omega\n   146→  -- Standard basis vectors: e₀ = 1 at index 0, e₁ = 1 at index 1\n   147→  let e₀ : Fin d → ℝ := fun i => if i.val = 0 then 1 else 0\n   148→  let e₁ : Fin d → ℝ := fun i => if i.val = 1 then 1 else 0\n   149→  -- E88 state: S = e₀ ⊗ e₀ᵀ (rank-1 outer product storing e₀ → e₀ association)\n   150→  let S : Matrix (Fin d) (Fin d) ℝ := Matrix.of (fun i j => e₀ i * e₀ j)\n   151→  use S, e₀, e₁\n   152→  constructor\n   153→  · -- e₀ ≠ e₁: they differ at index 0 (e₀(0) = 1, e₁(0) = 0)\n   154→    intro h\n   155→    have h00 := congr_fun h ⟨0, hd0⟩\n   156→    simp only [e₀, e₁] at h00\n   157→    norm_num at h00\n   158→  · -- e88ContentRead S e₀ ≠ e88ContentRead S e₁\n   159→    -- We show they differ at coordinate 0:\n   160→    --   (S · e₀)[0] = (e₀ ⊗ e₀ᵀ · e₀)[0] = e₀[0] · ‖e₀‖² = 1 · 1 = 1\n   161→    --   (S · e₁)[0] = (e₀ ⊗ e₀ᵀ · e₁)[0] = e₀[0] · (e₀ · e₁) = 1 · 0 = 0\n   162→    intro h_reads_eq\n   163→    -- Compute (S · e₀) at index 0 = 1\n   164→    have h_read0 : e88ContentRead S e₀ ⟨0, hd0⟩ = 1 := by\n   165→      simp only [e88ContentRead, Matrix.mulVec, dotProduct, S, Matrix.of_apply, e₀]\n   166→      -- Sum is: ∑ j, (if 0 = 0 then 1 else 0) * (if j.val = 0 then 1 else 0) *\n   167→      --                                          (if j.val = 0 then 1 else 0)\n   168→      -- = 1 * ∑ j, (if j.val = 0 then 1)²  = 1 * 1 = 1\n   169→      simp only [ite_true, one_mul]\n   170→      exact basis_self_inner_product d hd0\n   171→    -- Compute (S · e₁) at index 0 = 0\n   172→    have h_read1 : e88ContentRead S e₁ ⟨0, hd0⟩ = 0 := by\n   173→      simp only [e88ContentRead, Matrix.mulVec, dotProduct, S, Matrix.of_apply, e₀]\n   174→      -- Sum is: ∑ j, (if 0 = 0 then 1) * (if j.val = 0 then 1) * (if j.val = 1 then 1)\n   175→      -- = 1 * ∑ j, (if j.val = 0 then 1) * (if j.val = 1 then 1) = 1 * 0 = 0\n   176→      simp only [ite_true, one_mul]\n   177→      exact basis_inner_product_zero d\n   178→    -- Contradiction: from h_reads_eq, 1 = 0\n   179→    have := congr_fun h_reads_eq ⟨0, hd0⟩\n   180→    rw [h_read0, h_read1] at this\n   181→    norm_num at this\n   182→\n   183→/-! ## Part 3: Capacity Separation -/\n   184→\n   185→/-- **THEOREM 4: Capacity Separation**\n   186→\n   187→For D ≥ 2, E88 state scalars per head (D²) strictly exceeds E1H state\n   188→scalars per head (D). This is the quantitative foundation explaining E88's\n   189→empirical superiority over E1H.\n   190→\n   191→The extra D² - D = D(D-1) scalars per head enable:\n   192→- Richer associative memories (multiple key-value pairs per head)\n   193→- Content-addressable retrieval (S·q) not available to E1H\n   194→- More complex temporal patterns preserved across the sequence -/\n   195→theorem capacity_separation (d : ℕ) (hd : d ≥ 2) :\n   196→    E1H.e1hStateScalarsPerHead d < E1H.e88StateScalarsPerHead d :=\n   197→  E1H.e88_state_exceeds_e1h_state d hd\n   198→\n   199→/-- For D ≥ 2, E88 total state capacity (H × D²) strictly exceeds E1H (H × D) -/\n   200→theorem total_capacity_separation (numHeads d : ℕ) (hH : numHeads ≥ 1) (hd : d ≥ 2) :\n   201→    E1H.e1hTotalState numHeads d < E1H.e88TotalState numHeads d :=\n   202→  E1H.e88_total_state_exceeds_e1h numHeads d hH hd\n   203→\n   204→/-- The capacity advantage factor: E88 stores D times as many scalars per head -/\n   205→theorem capacity_factor (d : ℕ) :\n   206→    E1H.e88StateScalarsPerHead d = d * E1H.e1hStateScalarsPerHead d :=\n   207→  E1H.e88_vs_e1h_capacity_ratio d\n   208→\n   209→/-! ## Part 4: Explicit Separation Example (D = 2) -/\n   210→\n   211→/-- For D = 2: E88 has 4 scalar entries per head, E1H has 2. -/\n   212→theorem separation_example_d2 :\n   213→    E1H.e88StateScalarsPerHead 2 = 4 ∧\n   214→    E1H.e1hStateScalarsPerHead 2 = 2 ∧\n   215→    E1H.e1hStateScalarsPerHead 2 < E1H.e88StateScalarsPerHead 2 := by\n   216→  simp [E1H.e88StateScalarsPerHead, E1H.e1hStateScalarsPerHead]\n   217→\n   218→/-- The 4 standard basis matrices of ℝ^{2×2} are all distinct.\n   219→\n   220→These are 4 distinct E88 states (when D=2) that any mapping to E1H's\n   221→2-dimensional state space must collapse (pigeonhole: 4 states → 2 bins\n   222→means at least 2 states are indistinguishable by E1H). -/\n   223→theorem four_distinct_e88_states_d2 :\n   224→    ∃ (S₁ S₂ S₃ S₄ : Matrix (Fin 2) (Fin 2) ℝ),\n   225→      S₁ ≠ S₂ ∧ S₁ ≠ S₃ ∧ S₁ ≠ S₄ ∧ S₂ ≠ S₃ ∧ S₂ ≠ S₄ ∧ S₃ ≠ S₄ := by\n   226→  -- The four standard basis matrices for ℝ^{2×2}: eᵢⱼ = 1 at (i,j), 0 elsewhere\n   227→  refine ⟨Matrix.of (fun i j : Fin 2 => if i.val = 0 ∧ j.val = 0 then (1:ℝ) else 0),\n   228→          Matrix.of (fun i j : Fin 2 => if i.val = 0 ∧ j.val = 1 then (1:ℝ) else 0),\n   229→          Matrix.of (fun i j : Fin 2 => if i.val = 1 ∧ j.val = 0 then (1:ℝ) else 0),\n   230→          Matrix.of (fun i j : Fin 2 => if i.val = 1 ∧ j.val = 1 then (1:ℝ) else 0),\n   231→          ?_, ?_, ?_, ?_, ?_, ?_⟩\n   232→  -- For each pair, extract the distinguishing entry, then derive 1 = 0\n   233→  · intro h  -- e₀₀ ≠ e₀₁: differ at (0,0) where e₀₀=1 but e₀₁=0\n   234→    have := congr_fun (congr_fun h ⟨0, by norm_num⟩) ⟨0, by norm_num⟩\n   235→    simp [Matrix.of_apply] at this\n   236→  · intro h  -- e₀₀ ≠ e₁₀: differ at (0,0) where e₀₀=1 but e₁₀=0\n   237→    have := congr_fun (congr_fun h ⟨0, by norm_num⟩) ⟨0, by norm_num⟩\n   238→    simp [Matrix.of_apply] at this\n   239→  · intro h  -- e₀₀ ≠ e₁₁: differ at (0,0) where e₀₀=1 but e₁₁=0\n   240→    have := congr_fun (congr_fun h ⟨0, by norm_num⟩) ⟨0, by norm_num⟩\n   241→    simp [Matrix.of_apply] at this\n   242→  · intro h  -- e₀₁ ≠ e₁₀: differ at (0,1) where e₀₁=1 but e₁₀=0\n   243→    have := congr_fun (congr_fun h ⟨0, by norm_num⟩) ⟨1, by norm_num⟩\n   244→    simp [Matrix.of_apply] at this\n   245→  · intro h  -- e₀₁ ≠ e₁₁: differ at (0,1) where e₀₁=1 but e₁₁=0\n   246→    have := congr_fun (congr_fun h ⟨0, by norm_num⟩) ⟨1, by norm_num⟩\n   247→    simp [Matrix.of_apply] at this\n   248→  · intro h  -- e₁₀ ≠ e₁₁: differ at (1,0) where e₁₀=1 but e₁₁=0\n   249→    have := congr_fun (congr_fun h ⟨1, by norm_num⟩) ⟨0, by norm_num⟩\n   250→    simp [Matrix.of_apply] at this\n   251→\n   252→/-! ## Summary -/\n   253→\n   254→/-- **MAIN SUMMARY: All capacity separation results**\n   255→\n   256→E88 strictly exceeds E1H in state capacity for D ≥ 2:\n   257→1. E88 has D² scalar entries per head (vs D for E1H)\n   258→2. E88 supports content-addressable retrieval S·q (E1H cannot)\n   259→3. E88 state separates from E1H: D < D² for D ≥ 2\n   260→\n   261→This is the state capacity half of why E88 empirically outperforms E1H\n   262→(1.19 vs 1.10 perplexity at 32K tokens). -/\n   263→theorem e88_exceeds_e1h_capacity_summary (d : ℕ) (hd : d ≥ 2) :\n   264→    -- (1) E88 has D² scalar degrees of freedom per head\n   265→    Fintype.card (Fin d × Fin d) = d * d ∧\n   266→    -- (2) E1H has D scalar degrees of freedom per head\n   267→    Fintype.card (Fin d) = d ∧\n   268→    -- (3) E88 has strictly more DOF: D < D²\n   269→    Fintype.card (Fin d) < Fintype.card (Fin d × Fin d) ∧\n   270→    -- (4) Content-addressable: E88 can distinguish different queries; E1H cannot\n   271→    (∃ (S : Matrix (Fin d) (Fin d) ℝ) (q₁ q₂ : Fin d → ℝ),\n   272→      q₁ ≠ q₂ ∧ e88ContentRead S q₁ ≠ e88ContentRead S q₂) ∧\n   273→    -- (5) Scalar count separation: D < D² (proven via E1HDefinition)\n   274→    E1H.e1hStateScalarsPerHead d < E1H.e88StateScalarsPerHead d := by\n   275→  exact ⟨e88_capacity_d_squared d,\n   276→         e1h_capacity_d d,\n   277→         e88_dof_strictly_exceeds_e1h d hd,\n   278→         e88_addressable_e1h_not d hd,\n   279→         capacity_separation d hd⟩\n   280→\n   281→end CapacitySeparation\n   282→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"95379173-9fa9-4c3b-b84e-0caa1677a98b","uuid":"a2c491d6-d73b-43d4-b1a1-4495745255ec","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/home/erikg/elman-proofs/ElmanProofs/Expressivity/E88ExceedsE1HCapacity.lean","content":"/-\nCopyright (c) 2026 Elman Project. All rights reserved.\nReleased under Apache 2.0 license.\nAuthors: Elman Project Contributors\n-/\nimport Mathlib.LinearAlgebra.Matrix.NonsingularInverse\nimport Mathlib.Data.Matrix.Basic\nimport Mathlib.Analysis.Normed.Group.Basic\nimport Mathlib.Analysis.SpecialFunctions.Trigonometric.Basic\nimport Mathlib.Analysis.SpecialFunctions.ExpDeriv\nimport Mathlib.Topology.Basic\nimport ElmanProofs.Expressivity.E1HDefinition\n\n/-!\n# E88 Matrix State Strictly Exceeds E1H Vector State\n\nThis file proves the capacity separation between E88 and E1H architectures:\n- E88 head state is a D×D matrix with D² scalar entries per head\n- E1H head state is a D-vector with D scalar entries per head\n- For D ≥ 2: D² > D, so E88 has strictly more state capacity per head\n\n## Connection to Empirical Results\n\nE88 achieves 1.19 perplexity at 32K vs E1H's 1.10. The D-fold state capacity\nincrease enables E88 to maintain richer associative memories and longer-range\ndependencies across the sequence.\n\n## Main Theorems\n\n* `e88_capacity_d_squared` - E88 matrix state has D² degrees of freedom\n* `e1h_capacity_d` - E1H vector state has D degrees of freedom\n* `e88_addressable_e1h_not` - E88 supports S·q content-based retrieval; E1H cannot\n* `capacity_separation` - For D ≥ 2, E88 state scalars > E1H state scalars\n\n## Proof Strategy\n\n1. **Counting argument**: The index set for E88 state entries is `Fin D × Fin D`\n   (cardinality D²), while for E1H it is `Fin D` (cardinality D). For D ≥ 2, D² > D.\n\n2. **Addressability**: E88's matrix state S allows content-addressable retrieval\n   via S · q (matrix-vector product). We demonstrate concretely:\n   - Store S = e₀ ⊗ e₀ᵀ (outer product of first basis vector)\n   - Query with e₀ (first basis): retrieves e₀ (nonzero)\n   - Query with e₁ (second basis, orthogonal): retrieves 0\n   - Different queries → different results → content-addressable\n\n3. **Separation**: Uses the already-proven `E1H.e88_state_exceeds_e1h_state`\n   which shows D < D² for D ≥ 2 (proven in E1HDefinition.lean).\n\n-/\n\nnamespace CapacitySeparation\n\nopen Real Matrix Finset BigOperators\n\n/-! ## Part 1: Degrees of Freedom Counting -/\n\n/-- **THEOREM 1: E88 matrix state has D² degrees of freedom**\n\nEach E88 head state is a D×D matrix. The index set for its entries is\n`Fin D × Fin D`, which has cardinality D * D = D².\n\nThis quantifies the number of independent real parameters stored per E88 head. -/\ntheorem e88_capacity_d_squared (d : ℕ) :\n    Fintype.card (Fin d × Fin d) = d * d := by\n  simp [Fintype.card_prod, Fintype.card_fin]\n\n/-- **THEOREM 2: E1H vector state has D degrees of freedom**\n\nEach E1H head state is a D-dimensional vector. The index set is `Fin D`,\nwhich has cardinality D.\n\nThis quantifies the number of independent real parameters stored per E1H head. -/\ntheorem e1h_capacity_d (d : ℕ) :\n    Fintype.card (Fin d) = d := Fintype.card_fin d\n\n/-- For D ≥ 2, E88 has strictly more degrees of freedom than E1H:\n    D < D² (equivalently, D < D * D when D ≥ 2) -/\ntheorem e88_dof_strictly_exceeds_e1h (d : ℕ) (hd : d ≥ 2) :\n    Fintype.card (Fin d) < Fintype.card (Fin d × Fin d) := by\n  simp [Fintype.card_prod, Fintype.card_fin]\n  nlinarith\n\n/-! ## Part 2: Content-Addressable Retrieval -/\n\n/-- E88 content-addressable read: compute S · q\n\nE88's state S (a D×D matrix) can be \"queried\" with a vector q by computing\nthe matrix-vector product S · q. This is the fundamental retrieval mechanism:\n- If S accumulated outer products v_k ⊗ k^T for key-value pairs (k, v_k),\n  then S · q selects values weighted by key-query similarity. -/\nnoncomputable def e88ContentRead {d : ℕ} (S : Matrix (Fin d) (Fin d) ℝ)\n    (q : Fin d → ℝ) : Fin d → ℝ :=\n  S.mulVec q\n\n/-- Helper: inner product of orthogonal basis vectors is 0.\nFor the standard basis vectors e₀ (= 1 at index 0, 0 elsewhere) and\ne₁ (= 1 at index 1, 0 elsewhere), their inner product is 0. -/\nprivate theorem basis_inner_product_zero (d : ℕ) :\n    ∑ j : Fin d, (if j.val = 0 then (1:ℝ) else 0) * (if j.val = 1 then 1 else 0) = 0 := by\n  apply Finset.sum_eq_zero\n  intro j _\n  split_ifs with h0 h1\n  · -- j.val = 0 and j.val = 1: impossible\n    exact absurd (h0.symm.trans h1) (by decide)\n  · ring\n  · ring\n  · ring\n\n/-- Helper: inner product of e₀ with itself is 1. -/\nprivate theorem basis_self_inner_product (d : ℕ) (hd0 : 0 < d) :\n    ∑ j : Fin d, (if j.val = 0 then (1:ℝ) else 0) * (if j.val = 0 then 1 else 0) = 1 := by\n  -- Simplify (if p then 1 else 0) * (if p then 1 else 0) = if p then 1 else 0\n  have h_sq : ∀ j : Fin d, (if j.val = 0 then (1:ℝ) else 0) * (if j.val = 0 then 1 else 0) =\n                             if j.val = 0 then 1 else 0 := fun j => by split_ifs <;> ring\n  simp_rw [h_sq]\n  -- Convert j.val = 0 condition to j = ⟨0, hd0⟩ for Fin d\n  have h_conv : ∀ j : Fin d, (if j.val = 0 then (1:ℝ) else 0) = if j = ⟨0, hd0⟩ then 1 else 0 :=\n    fun j => by simp [Fin.ext_iff]\n  simp_rw [h_conv]\n  -- Apply sum_ite_eq: ∑ j in univ, if j = a then f j else 0 = if a ∈ univ then f a else 0\n  simp\n\n/-- **THEOREM 3: E88 supports S·q content-based retrieval that E1H cannot**\n\nWe formally demonstrate E88's content-addressable retrieval by constructing:\n- A state S = e₀ ⊗ e₀ᵀ (outer product of the first standard basis vector)\n- Two queries e₀ ≠ e₁ (orthogonal basis vectors)\n- S · e₀ = e₀ (nonzero: retrieves the stored association)\n- S · e₁ = 0   (zero: orthogonal query finds nothing)\n\nSo different queries retrieve different information from the same state.\n\n**Why E1H cannot do this**: E1H's state is a D-vector h, not a matrix.\nAny \"read\" operation on h produces the same information (or a fixed linear\nprojection thereof) regardless of any \"query\" vector — there is no matrix\nto multiply against, so no key-based addressing is possible.\n\nThis difference explains why E88 can implement associative memory patterns\n(key-value retrieval) that E1H fundamentally cannot. -/\ntheorem e88_addressable_e1h_not (d : ℕ) (hd : d ≥ 2) :\n    ∃ (S : Matrix (Fin d) (Fin d) ℝ) (q₁ q₂ : Fin d → ℝ),\n      q₁ ≠ q₂ ∧ e88ContentRead S q₁ ≠ e88ContentRead S q₂ := by\n  have hd0 : 0 < d := by omega\n  have hd1 : 1 < d := by omega\n  -- Standard basis vectors: e₀ = 1 at index 0, e₁ = 1 at index 1\n  let e₀ : Fin d → ℝ := fun i => if i.val = 0 then 1 else 0\n  let e₁ : Fin d → ℝ := fun i => if i.val = 1 then 1 else 0\n  -- E88 state: S = e₀ ⊗ e₀ᵀ (rank-1 outer product storing e₀ → e₀ association)\n  let S : Matrix (Fin d) (Fin d) ℝ := Matrix.of (fun i j => e₀ i * e₀ j)\n  use S, e₀, e₁\n  constructor\n  · -- e₀ ≠ e₁: they differ at index 0 (e₀(0) = 1, e₁(0) = 0)\n    intro h\n    have h00 := congr_fun h ⟨0, hd0⟩\n    simp only [e₀, e₁] at h00\n    norm_num at h00\n  · -- e88ContentRead S e₀ ≠ e88ContentRead S e₁\n    -- We show they differ at coordinate 0:\n    --   (S · e₀)[0] = (e₀ ⊗ e₀ᵀ · e₀)[0] = e₀[0] · ‖e₀‖² = 1 · 1 = 1\n    --   (S · e₁)[0] = (e₀ ⊗ e₀ᵀ · e₁)[0] = e₀[0] · (e₀ · e₁) = 1 · 0 = 0\n    intro h_reads_eq\n    -- Compute (S · e₀) at index 0 = 1\n    have h_read0 : e88ContentRead S e₀ ⟨0, hd0⟩ = 1 := by\n      simp only [e88ContentRead, Matrix.mulVec, dotProduct, S, Matrix.of_apply, e₀]\n      -- Sum is: ∑ j, (if 0 = 0 then 1 else 0) * (if j.val = 0 then 1 else 0) *\n      --                                          (if j.val = 0 then 1 else 0)\n      -- = 1 * ∑ j, (if j.val = 0 then 1)²  = 1 * 1 = 1\n      simp only [ite_true, one_mul]\n      exact basis_self_inner_product d hd0\n    -- Compute (S · e₁) at index 0 = 0\n    have h_read1 : e88ContentRead S e₁ ⟨0, hd0⟩ = 0 := by\n      simp only [e88ContentRead, Matrix.mulVec, dotProduct, S, Matrix.of_apply, e₀]\n      -- Sum is: ∑ j, (if 0 = 0 then 1) * (if j.val = 0 then 1) * (if j.val = 1 then 1)\n      -- = 1 * ∑ j, (if j.val = 0 then 1) * (if j.val = 1 then 1) = 1 * 0 = 0\n      simp only [ite_true, one_mul]\n      exact basis_inner_product_zero d\n    -- Contradiction: from h_reads_eq, 1 = 0\n    have := congr_fun h_reads_eq ⟨0, hd0⟩\n    rw [h_read0, h_read1] at this\n    norm_num at this\n\n/-! ## Part 3: Capacity Separation -/\n\n/-- **THEOREM 4: Capacity Separation**\n\nFor D ≥ 2, E88 state scalars per head (D²) strictly exceeds E1H state\nscalars per head (D). This is the quantitative foundation explaining E88's\nempirical superiority over E1H.\n\nThe extra D² - D = D(D-1) scalars per head enable:\n- Richer associative memories (multiple key-value pairs per head)\n- Content-addressable retrieval (S·q) not available to E1H\n- More complex temporal patterns preserved across the sequence -/\ntheorem capacity_separation (d : ℕ) (hd : d ≥ 2) :\n    E1H.e1hStateScalarsPerHead d < E1H.e88StateScalarsPerHead d :=\n  E1H.e88_state_exceeds_e1h_state d hd\n\n/-- For D ≥ 2, E88 total state capacity (H × D²) strictly exceeds E1H (H × D) -/\ntheorem total_capacity_separation (numHeads d : ℕ) (hH : numHeads ≥ 1) (hd : d ≥ 2) :\n    E1H.e1hTotalState numHeads d < E1H.e88TotalState numHeads d :=\n  E1H.e88_total_state_exceeds_e1h numHeads d hH hd\n\n/-- The capacity advantage factor: E88 stores D times as many scalars per head -/\ntheorem capacity_factor (d : ℕ) :\n    E1H.e88StateScalarsPerHead d = d * E1H.e1hStateScalarsPerHead d :=\n  E1H.e88_vs_e1h_capacity_ratio d\n\n/-! ## Part 4: Explicit Separation Example (D = 2) -/\n\n/-- For D = 2: E88 has 4 scalar entries per head, E1H has 2. -/\ntheorem separation_example_d2 :\n    E1H.e88StateScalarsPerHead 2 = 4 ∧\n    E1H.e1hStateScalarsPerHead 2 = 2 ∧\n    E1H.e1hStateScalarsPerHead 2 < E1H.e88StateScalarsPerHead 2 := by\n  simp [E1H.e88StateScalarsPerHead, E1H.e1hStateScalarsPerHead]\n\n/-- The 4 standard basis matrices of ℝ^{2×2} are all distinct.\n\nThese are 4 distinct E88 states (when D=2) that any mapping to E1H's\n2-dimensional state space must collapse (pigeonhole: 4 states → 2 bins\nmeans at least 2 states are indistinguishable by E1H). -/\ntheorem four_distinct_e88_states_d2 :\n    ∃ (S₁ S₂ S₃ S₄ : Matrix (Fin 2) (Fin 2) ℝ),\n      S₁ ≠ S₂ ∧ S₁ ≠ S₃ ∧ S₁ ≠ S₄ ∧ S₂ ≠ S₃ ∧ S₂ ≠ S₄ ∧ S₃ ≠ S₄ := by\n  -- The four standard basis matrices for ℝ^{2×2}: eᵢⱼ = 1 at (i,j), 0 elsewhere\n  refine ⟨Matrix.of (fun i j : Fin 2 => if i.val = 0 ∧ j.val = 0 then (1:ℝ) else 0),\n          Matrix.of (fun i j : Fin 2 => if i.val = 0 ∧ j.val = 1 then (1:ℝ) else 0),\n          Matrix.of (fun i j : Fin 2 => if i.val = 1 ∧ j.val = 0 then (1:ℝ) else 0),\n          Matrix.of (fun i j : Fin 2 => if i.val = 1 ∧ j.val = 1 then (1:ℝ) else 0),\n          ?_, ?_, ?_, ?_, ?_, ?_⟩\n  -- For each pair, extract the distinguishing entry, then derive 1 = 0\n  · intro h  -- e₀₀ ≠ e₀₁: differ at (0,0) where e₀₀=1 but e₀₁=0\n    have := congr_fun (congr_fun h ⟨0, by norm_num⟩) ⟨0, by norm_num⟩\n    simp [Matrix.of_apply] at this\n  · intro h  -- e₀₀ ≠ e₁₀: differ at (0,0) where e₀₀=1 but e₁₀=0\n    have := congr_fun (congr_fun h ⟨0, by norm_num⟩) ⟨0, by norm_num⟩\n    simp [Matrix.of_apply] at this\n  · intro h  -- e₀₀ ≠ e₁₁: differ at (0,0) where e₀₀=1 but e₁₁=0\n    have := congr_fun (congr_fun h ⟨0, by norm_num⟩) ⟨0, by norm_num⟩\n    simp [Matrix.of_apply] at this\n  · intro h  -- e₀₁ ≠ e₁₀: differ at (0,1) where e₀₁=1 but e₁₀=0\n    have := congr_fun (congr_fun h ⟨0, by norm_num⟩) ⟨1, by norm_num⟩\n    simp [Matrix.of_apply] at this\n  · intro h  -- e₀₁ ≠ e₁₁: differ at (0,1) where e₀₁=1 but e₁₁=0\n    have := congr_fun (congr_fun h ⟨0, by norm_num⟩) ⟨1, by norm_num⟩\n    simp [Matrix.of_apply] at this\n  · intro h  -- e₁₀ ≠ e₁₁: differ at (1,0) where e₁₀=1 but e₁₁=0\n    have := congr_fun (congr_fun h ⟨1, by norm_num⟩) ⟨0, by norm_num⟩\n    simp [Matrix.of_apply] at this\n\n/-! ## Summary -/\n\n/-- **MAIN SUMMARY: All capacity separation results**\n\nE88 strictly exceeds E1H in state capacity for D ≥ 2:\n1. E88 has D² scalar entries per head (vs D for E1H)\n2. E88 supports content-addressable retrieval S·q (E1H cannot)\n3. E88 state separates from E1H: D < D² for D ≥ 2\n\nThis is the state capacity half of why E88 empirically outperforms E1H\n(1.19 vs 1.10 perplexity at 32K tokens). -/\ntheorem e88_exceeds_e1h_capacity_summary (d : ℕ) (hd : d ≥ 2) :\n    -- (1) E88 has D² scalar degrees of freedom per head\n    Fintype.card (Fin d × Fin d) = d * d ∧\n    -- (2) E1H has D scalar degrees of freedom per head\n    Fintype.card (Fin d) = d ∧\n    -- (3) E88 has strictly more DOF: D < D²\n    Fintype.card (Fin d) < Fintype.card (Fin d × Fin d) ∧\n    -- (4) Content-addressable: E88 can distinguish different queries; E1H cannot\n    (∃ (S : Matrix (Fin d) (Fin d) ℝ) (q₁ q₂ : Fin d → ℝ),\n      q₁ ≠ q₂ ∧ e88ContentRead S q₁ ≠ e88ContentRead S q₂) ∧\n    -- (5) Scalar count separation: D < D² (proven via E1HDefinition)\n    E1H.e1hStateScalarsPerHead d < E1H.e88StateScalarsPerHead d := by\n  exact ⟨e88_capacity_d_squared d,\n         e1h_capacity_d d,\n         e88_dof_strictly_exceeds_e1h d hd,\n         e88_addressable_e1h_not d hd,\n         capacity_separation d hd⟩\n\nend CapacitySeparation\n","numLines":282,"startLine":1,"totalLines":282}}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01L48idaQSS8H3FaoT1QfFB9","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01PPRMT1zMrtEPg8X3H2xRRW","name":"Read","input":{"file_path":"/home/erikg/elman-proofs/ElmanProofs/Expressivity/E1HTemporalTheorems.lean"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":427,"cache_read_input_tokens":28457,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":427},"output_tokens":18,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"95379173-9fa9-4c3b-b84e-0caa1677a98b","uuid":"a26c0ffa-5ede-48c6-8152-2747a5520601"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01PPRMT1zMrtEPg8X3H2xRRW","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→/-\n     2→Copyright (c) 2026 Elman Project. All rights reserved.\n     3→Released under Apache 2.0 license.\n     4→Authors: Elman Project Contributors\n     5→-/\n     6→import Mathlib.LinearAlgebra.Matrix.NonsingularInverse\n     7→import Mathlib.Data.Matrix.Basic\n     8→import Mathlib.Analysis.Normed.Group.Basic\n     9→import Mathlib.Analysis.SpecialFunctions.Trigonometric.Basic\n    10→import Mathlib.Analysis.SpecialFunctions.ExpDeriv\n    11→import Mathlib.Topology.Basic\n    12→import ElmanProofs.Activations.Lipschitz\n    13→import ElmanProofs.Expressivity.E1HDefinition\n    14→import ElmanProofs.Expressivity.TanhSaturation\n    15→import ElmanProofs.Expressivity.AttentionPersistence\n    16→\n    17→/-!\n    18→# E1H Shares Temporal Expressivity with E88\n    19→\n    20→This file proves that E1H has the same temporal compositional depth and expressivity\n    21→as E88. The key insight is that E1H's update rule:\n    22→\n    23→  h_t = tanh(W_x · x_t + W_h · h_{t-1} + b)\n    24→\n    25→with appropriate parameter choices reduces to the SAME scalar tanh dynamics already\n    26→studied in TanhSaturation.lean and AttentionPersistence.lean.\n    27→\n    28→## Strategy\n    29→\n    30→For a 1-dimensional E1H head (headDim = 1), the update becomes:\n    31→\n    32→  h_t[0] = tanh(W_x[0,0] · x_t[0] + W_h[0,0] · h_{t-1}[0] + b[0])\n    33→\n    34→which is precisely `TanhSaturation.tanhRecurrence α b S` with:\n    35→  - α = W_h[0,0]  (plays role of E88's α: recurrence strength)\n    36→  - b = W_x[0,0] · x_t[0] + b[0]  (plays role of E88's δ·k: input-dependent bias)\n    37→\n    38→This means all temporal expressivity results proven for E88's tanh dynamics\n    39→transfer directly to E1H by choosing W_h and W_x to match the E88 parameters.\n    40→\n    41→## Main Results\n    42→\n    43→* `e1h_has_depth_T` - E1H has compositional depth T (same as E88)\n    44→* `e1h_1d_is_tanh_recurrence` - 1D E1H head IS the scalar tanh recurrence\n    45→* `e1h_can_compute_parity` - E1H can compute running parity (same sign-flip mechanism)\n    46→* `e1h_can_threshold` - E1H can accumulate and threshold via tanh saturation\n    47→* `e1h_heads_independent_temporal` - E1H heads evolve independently\n    48→* `e1h_e88_temporal_equivalence` - E1H and E88 have equivalent temporal expressivity\n    49→\n    50→## References\n    51→\n    52→- TanhSaturation.lean: `tanhRecurrence`, `tanhRecurrence_is_contraction`,\n    53→  `near_saturation_low_gradient`, `e88_temporal_capabilities`\n    54→- AttentionPersistence.lean: `tanhRecur`, `alert_forward_invariant`, `latched_state_robust`\n    55→- E1HDefinition.lean: `e1hHeadUpdate`, `e1h_heads_independent`, `e1h_state_bounded`,\n    56→  `e1h_temporal_depth_equals_e88`\n    57→\n    58→-/\n    59→\n    60→namespace E1HTemporalTheorems\n    61→\n    62→open Real Matrix Finset BigOperators E1H TanhSaturation AttentionPersistence\n    63→\n    64→/-! ## Specific E1H Heads for Temporal Expressivity Theorems -/\n    65→\n    66→/-- E1H head implementing sign-flip parity dynamics.\n    67→    W_h[0,0] = 1 (identity recurrence), W_x[0,0] = -3 (sign-flip on x=1).\n    68→    Identical construction to E88Definition.e88_can_compute_parity (α=1, δ=-3). -/\n    69→noncomputable def e1hParityHead : E1HHead 1 1 where\n    70→  inputProj := (-3.0 : ℝ) • (1 : Matrix (Fin 1) (Fin 1) ℝ)\n    71→  recurrenceWeight := (1 : Matrix (Fin 1) (Fin 1) ℝ)\n    72→  bias := fun _ => 0\n    73→\n    74→/-- E1H head implementing threshold/saturation dynamics.\n    75→    W_h[0,0] = 1.5 ∈ (1, 2): saturation regime from AttentionPersistence.lean.\n    76→    By e1h_1d_is_tanh_recurrence, this equals tanhRecur 1.5 from AttentionPersistence. -/\n    77→noncomputable def e1hThresholdHead : E1HHead 1 1 where\n    78→  inputProj := (0 : Matrix (Fin 1) (Fin 1) ℝ)\n    79→  recurrenceWeight := (1.5 : ℝ) • (1 : Matrix (Fin 1) (Fin 1) ℝ)\n    80→  bias := fun _ => 0\n    81→\n    82→@[simp] lemma e1hThresholdHead_rw_val :\n    83→    e1hThresholdHead.recurrenceWeight 0 0 = 1.5 := by\n    84→  simp [e1hThresholdHead, Matrix.smul_apply, Matrix.one_apply]\n    85→\n    86→/-! ## Part 1: E1H Compositional Depth -/\n    87→\n    88→/-- **THEOREM 1: E1H Has Compositional Depth T**\n    89→\n    90→After T timesteps, the E1H state is a T-fold composition of the nonlinear tanh update.\n    91→This matches E88's compositional depth exactly.\n    92→\n    93→Unlike linear-temporal models (fixed depth 1), both E1H and E88\n    94→build depth proportional to sequence length T. -/\n    95→theorem e1h_has_depth_T (T : ℕ) (h_T : T > 1) :\n    96→    -- E1H compositional depth equals sequence length T\n    97→    let e1h_depth := T\n    98→    -- Linear-temporal models have fixed depth 1\n    99→    let linear_depth := 1\n   100→    -- E1H strictly exceeds linear depth (same bound as E88)\n   101→    e1h_depth > linear_depth ∧\n   102→    -- E1H depth equals E88 depth\n   103→    e1h_depth = T := ⟨h_T, rfl⟩\n   104→\n   105→/-- E1H and E88 have the same compositional depth T per layer.\n   106→    Both apply exactly T nonlinear recurrence steps. -/\n   107→theorem e1h_temporal_depth_eq_e88 (T : ℕ) :\n   108→    let e1h_depth := T; let e88_depth := T; e1h_depth = e88_depth := rfl\n   109→\n   110→/-! ## Part 2: E1H 1D Head Reduction to Scalar Tanh Recurrence -/\n   111→\n   112→/-- **Key structural lemma**: a 1-dimensional E1H head update IS the scalar tanh recurrence.\n   113→\n   114→For headDim = 1:\n   115→  e1hHeadUpdate head h x 0 = tanh(W_x[0,0]·x[0] + W_h[0,0]·h[0] + b[0])\n   116→                            = tanhRecurrence (W_h[0,0]) (W_x[0,0]·x[0] + b[0]) (h[0])\n   117→\n   118→This lets E1H inherit all E88 temporal properties proven in TanhSaturation.lean\n   119→(sign-flip dynamics, saturation, etc.) by matching W_h[0,0] ↔ E88's α and\n   120→W_x[0,0] ↔ E88's δ. -/\n   121→theorem e1h_1d_is_tanh_recurrence (head : E1HHead 1 1)\n   122→    (h_state : Fin 1 → ℝ) (x : Fin 1 → ℝ) :\n   123→    e1hHeadUpdate head h_state x 0 =\n   124→    tanhRecurrence\n   125→      (head.recurrenceWeight 0 0)\n   126→      (head.inputProj.mulVec x 0 + head.bias 0)\n   127→      (h_state 0) := by\n   128→  simp only [e1hHeadUpdate, vecTanh, tanhRecurrence]\n   129→  congr 1\n   130→  have hmv : head.recurrenceWeight.mulVec h_state 0 =\n   131→      head.recurrenceWeight 0 0 * h_state 0 := by\n   132→    show ∑ j : Fin 1, head.recurrenceWeight 0 j * h_state j =\n   133→         head.recurrenceWeight 0 0 * h_state 0\n   134→    rw [Fin.sum_univ_one]\n   135→  rw [hmv]; ring\n   136→\n   137→/-- E1H's W_h[0,0] plays the same role as E88's α: it's the contraction factor. -/\n   138→theorem e1h_wh_plays_role_of_alpha (head : E1HHead 1 1) :\n   139→    let α := head.recurrenceWeight 0 0\n   140→    ∀ b S₁ S₂ : ℝ, |α| < 1 →\n   141→      |tanhRecurrence α b S₁ - tanhRecurrence α b S₂| ≤ |α| * |S₁ - S₂| :=\n   142→  fun b S₁ S₂ hα => TanhSaturation.tanhRecurrence_is_contraction _ hα b S₁ S₂\n   143→\n   144→/-! ## Part 3: E1H Can Compute Running Parity -/\n   145→\n   146→/-- **THEOREM 2: E1H Can Compute Running Parity**\n   147→\n   148→E1H can compute running parity using the same tanh sign-flip mechanism as E88.\n   149→\n   150→Construction (e1hParityHead): W_h[0,0] = 1.0, W_x[0,0] = -3.0.\n   151→By e1h_1d_is_tanh_recurrence, this equals E88's scalar dynamics tanh(h - 3·x).\n   152→The sign-flip analysis from TanhSaturation.e88_computes_running_parity applies directly.\n   153→\n   154→The state at each step is bounded in (-1, 1) by tanh, and tracks parity via sign\n   155→(near +1 for even parity, near -1 for odd parity — same as E88). -/\n   156→theorem e1h_can_compute_parity :\n   157→    ∃ (head : E1HHead 1 1),\n   158→    -- The head implements sign-flip dynamics identical to E88's parity head\n   159→    ∀ T : ℕ, ∀ inputs : Fin T → (Fin 1 → ℝ),\n   160→      (∀ t, inputs t 0 = 0 ∨ inputs t 0 = 1) →\n   161→    ∀ t : Fin T,\n   162→    let stateAtT := e1hHeadStateAfterT head (t.val + 1)\n   163→      (fun s => if h : s.val < T then inputs ⟨s.val, h⟩ else fun _ => 0)\n   164→    -- State magnitude < 1: E1H state is tanh-bounded (same as E88)\n   165→    -- Full parity encoding proof: same as TanhSaturation.e88_computes_running_parity\n   166→    |stateAtT 0| < 1 := by\n   167→  use e1hParityHead\n   168→  intro T inputs _h_binary t\n   169→  -- The state after any number of tanh-based updates is bounded in (-1, 1)\n   170→  -- This uses E1H.e1h_state_bounded: each update output is tanh-bounded\n   171→  -- Full proof requires induction on the foldl; the final step IS an e1hHeadUpdate\n   172→  -- so e1h_state_bounded applies (same argument as E88Definition.e88_can_compute_parity)\n   173→  sorry -- Induction on e1hHeadStateAfterT: each step applies e1hHeadUpdate,\n   174→        -- bounded output follows from Activation.tanh_bounded\n   175→\n   176→/-- E1H sign-flip parity head has the same dynamics as E88's parity head.\n   177→    The 1D reduction (e1h_1d_is_tanh_recurrence) makes this immediate:\n   178→    both compute tanh(α·h + δ·x) with α≈1, δ≈-3. -/\n   179→theorem e1h_parity_equals_e88_parity :\n   180→    -- E1H parity dynamics: W_h[0,0] = 1, W_x[0,0] = -3 (same regime as E88)\n   181→    ∃ (α β : ℝ), 0 < α ∧ α < 4 ∧ 0 < β ∧ β < 4 :=\n   182→  ⟨1, 3, by norm_num, by norm_num, by norm_num, by norm_num⟩\n   183→\n   184→/-! ## Part 4: E1H Can Threshold (Accumulation + Saturation) -/\n   185→\n   186→/-- **THEOREM 3: E1H Can Threshold (Same Accumulation + Saturation as E88)**\n   187→\n   188→E1H implements accumulate-and-threshold via tanh saturation.\n   189→\n   190→The e1hThresholdHead has W_h[0,0] = 1.5 ∈ (1, 2).\n   191→By e1h_1d_is_tanh_recurrence, this equals tanhRecur 1.5 from AttentionPersistence.lean.\n   192→AttentionPersistence.alert_forward_invariant proves the forward-invariant alert basin\n   193→property for α ∈ (1, 2) — this applies directly to E1H's threshold head.\n   194→\n   195→This is the same mechanism as TanhSaturation.alert_state_is_absorbing for E88. -/\n   196→theorem e1h_can_threshold :\n   197→    ∃ (head : E1HHead 1 1) (θ : ℝ),\n   198→      0 < θ ∧ θ < 1 ∧\n   199→      let α := head.recurrenceWeight 0 0\n   200→      1 < α ∧ α < 2 := by\n   201→  refine ⟨e1hThresholdHead, 0.76, by norm_num, by norm_num, ?_, ?_⟩\n   202→  · -- 1 < W_h[0,0] = 1.5\n   203→    simp only [e1hThresholdHead_rw_val]; norm_num\n   204→  · -- W_h[0,0] = 1.5 < 2\n   205→    simp only [e1hThresholdHead_rw_val]; norm_num\n   206→\n   207→/-- For e1hThresholdHead, the 1D update equals tanhRecur α.\n   208→\n   209→This connects E1H threshold dynamics directly to AttentionPersistence.lean. -/\n   210→theorem e1h_threshold_reduces_to_tanhRecur (h_state : Fin 1 → ℝ) :\n   211→    e1hHeadUpdate e1hThresholdHead h_state (fun _ => 0) 0 =\n   212→    AttentionPersistence.tanhRecur 1.5 (h_state 0) := by\n   213→  -- By e1h_1d_is_tanh_recurrence: update = tanhRecurrence (W_h[0,0]) (W_x[0,0]·0 + b[0]) (h[0])\n   214→  -- W_h[0,0] = 1.5, W_x[0,0]·0 = 0, b[0] = 0, so update = tanh(1.5 · h[0])\n   215→  -- AttentionPersistence.tanhRecur 1.5 h = tanh(1.5 · h)\n   216→  simp only [e1hHeadUpdate, vecTanh, AttentionPersistence.tanhRecur, e1hThresholdHead]\n   217→  congr 1\n   218→  -- Need: ((-3) • 1).mulVec (fun _ => 0) 0 + (1.5 • 1).mulVec h_state 0 + 0 = 1.5 * h_state 0\n   219→  -- Wait: the threshold head has inputProj = 0 (not -3 • 1)\n   220→  -- inputProj = 0, recurrenceWeight = 1.5 • 1, bias = 0\n   221→  -- So: 0.mulVec (fun _ => 0) 0 + (1.5 • 1).mulVec h_state 0 + 0 = 1.5 * h_state 0\n   222→  show (0 : Matrix (Fin 1) (Fin 1) ℝ).mulVec (fun _ => 0) 0 +\n   223→       ((1.5 : ℝ) • (1 : Matrix (Fin 1) (Fin 1) ℝ)).mulVec h_state 0 +\n   224→       (0 : Fin 1 → ℝ) 0 = 1.5 * h_state 0\n   225→  simp only [Matrix.zero_mulVec, Pi.zero_apply, zero_add, add_zero]\n   226→  show ∑ j : Fin 1, ((1.5 : ℝ) • (1 : Matrix (Fin 1) (Fin 1) ℝ)) 0 j * h_state j =\n   227→       1.5 * h_state 0\n   228→  rw [Fin.sum_univ_one]\n   229→  simp [Matrix.smul_apply, Matrix.one_apply]\n   230→\n   231→/-! ## Part 5: E1H Heads Evolve Independently -/\n   232→\n   233→/-- **THEOREM 4: E1H Heads Evolve Independently**\n   234→\n   235→Each E1H head's temporal dynamics are fully independent of other heads.\n   236→This is the same structural property as E88's head independence\n   237→(E88Definition.e88_heads_independent, MultiHeadTemporalIndependence.lean).\n   238→\n   239→Consequence: H independent E1H heads provide H independent temporal channels,\n   240→each capable of tracking a different temporal pattern simultaneously. -/\n   241→theorem e1h_heads_independent_temporal {numHeads : ℕ} (model : E1HModel numHeads d d) (T : ℕ)\n   242→    (inputs : Fin T → (Fin d → ℝ)) (h1 h2 : Fin numHeads) (h_neq : h1 ≠ h2) :\n   243→    ∀ (head2' : E1HHead d d),\n   244→      e1hHeadStateAfterT (model.heads h1) T inputs =\n   245→      e1hHeadStateAfterT\n   246→        ({ model with heads := fun i => if i = h2 then head2' else model.heads i }.heads h1)\n   247→        T inputs :=\n   248→  fun head2' => E1H.e1h_heads_independent model T inputs h1 h2 h_neq head2'\n   249→\n   250→/-- Multi-head E1H state decomposes into independent per-head trajectories. -/\n   251→theorem e1h_multihead_parallel_channels {H : ℕ} (model : E1HModel H d d) (T : ℕ)\n   252→    (inputs : Fin T → (Fin d → ℝ)) :\n   253→    ∀ hIdx : Fin H,\n   254→      (e1hMultiHeadState model T inputs) hIdx =\n   255→      e1hHeadStateAfterT (model.heads hIdx) T inputs (fun _ => 0) :=\n   256→  fun _ => rfl\n   257→\n   258→/-! ## Part 6: E1H Temporal Expressivity Equivalence Summary -/\n   259→\n   260→/-- **MAIN THEOREM: E1H and E88 Have Equivalent Temporal Expressivity**\n   261→\n   262→E1H and E88 share all temporal expressivity properties:\n   263→\n   264→1. **Compositional Depth T**: Both compute T sequential nonlinear compositions\n   265→   (e1h_has_depth_T, e1h_temporal_depth_eq_e88)\n   266→\n   267→2. **Sign-Flip / Parity**: Both implement XOR dynamics via tanh sign-flipping\n   268→   (e1h_can_compute_parity; construction matches E88Definition.e88_can_compute_parity)\n   269→\n   270→3. **Accumulation + Saturation**: Both have forward-invariant alert basins\n   271→   (e1h_can_threshold; follows from AttentionPersistence.alert_forward_invariant\n   272→    via e1h_threshold_reduces_to_tanhRecur)\n   273→\n   274→4. **Head Independence**: Both have H independent temporal channels\n   275→   (e1h_heads_independent_temporal; same as E88Definition.e88_heads_independent)\n   276→\n   277→The DIFFERENCE is in capacity (not temporal expressivity):\n   278→- E88: D×D matrix state per head (D² scalars)\n   279→- E1H: D-vector state per head (D scalars)\n   280→- E88 has D× more state capacity (E1HDefinition.e88_vs_e1h_capacity_ratio)\n   281→\n   282→Temporal expressivity is the same because depth T depends on recurrence steps,\n   283→not state dimension. -/\n   284→theorem e1h_e88_temporal_equivalence (T : ℕ) (h_T : T > 1) :\n   285→    -- 1. Same compositional depth\n   286→    (let e1h_depth := T; let e88_depth := T; e1h_depth = e88_depth) ∧\n   287→    -- 2. E1H parity: state is tanh-bounded (same mechanism as E88)\n   288→    (∃ (head : E1HHead 1 1), ∀ (state : Fin 1 → ℝ) (x : Fin 1 → ℝ),\n   289→       |e1hHeadUpdate head state x 0| < 1) ∧\n   290→    -- 3. E1H threshold: saturation regime α ∈ (1, 2) exists (same as E88)\n   291→    (∃ (head : E1HHead 1 1) (θ : ℝ), 0 < θ ∧ θ < 1 ∧\n   292→       let α := head.recurrenceWeight 0 0; 1 < α ∧ α < 2) ∧\n   293→    -- 4. Head independence (same structural property as E88)\n   294→    (∀ {numHeads : ℕ} (model : E1HModel numHeads d d) (t1 t2 : Fin numHeads),\n   295→       t1 ≠ t2 →\n   296→       ∀ (head2' : E1HHead d d),\n   297→         e1hHeadStateAfterT (model.heads t1) T (fun _ => fun _ => 0) =\n   298→         e1hHeadStateAfterT\n   299→           ({ model with heads := fun i => if i = t2 then head2' else model.heads i }.heads t1)\n   300→           T (fun _ => fun _ => 0)) := by\n   301→  refine ⟨rfl, ?_, e1h_can_threshold, ?_⟩\n   302→  · -- 2. Parity: each single tanh update is bounded by e1h_state_bounded\n   303→    exact ⟨e1hParityHead, fun state x => E1H.e1h_state_bounded e1hParityHead state x 0⟩\n   304→  · -- 4. Head independence from E1HDefinition.lean\n   305→    intro numHeads model t1 t2 h_neq head2'\n   306→    exact E1H.e1h_heads_independent model T _ t1 t2 h_neq head2'\n   307→\n   308→end E1HTemporalTheorems\n   309→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"95379173-9fa9-4c3b-b84e-0caa1677a98b","uuid":"644d11eb-57b3-495e-9f33-f0f293a2bc74","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/home/erikg/elman-proofs/ElmanProofs/Expressivity/E1HTemporalTheorems.lean","content":"/-\nCopyright (c) 2026 Elman Project. All rights reserved.\nReleased under Apache 2.0 license.\nAuthors: Elman Project Contributors\n-/\nimport Mathlib.LinearAlgebra.Matrix.NonsingularInverse\nimport Mathlib.Data.Matrix.Basic\nimport Mathlib.Analysis.Normed.Group.Basic\nimport Mathlib.Analysis.SpecialFunctions.Trigonometric.Basic\nimport Mathlib.Analysis.SpecialFunctions.ExpDeriv\nimport Mathlib.Topology.Basic\nimport ElmanProofs.Activations.Lipschitz\nimport ElmanProofs.Expressivity.E1HDefinition\nimport ElmanProofs.Expressivity.TanhSaturation\nimport ElmanProofs.Expressivity.AttentionPersistence\n\n/-!\n# E1H Shares Temporal Expressivity with E88\n\nThis file proves that E1H has the same temporal compositional depth and expressivity\nas E88. The key insight is that E1H's update rule:\n\n  h_t = tanh(W_x · x_t + W_h · h_{t-1} + b)\n\nwith appropriate parameter choices reduces to the SAME scalar tanh dynamics already\nstudied in TanhSaturation.lean and AttentionPersistence.lean.\n\n## Strategy\n\nFor a 1-dimensional E1H head (headDim = 1), the update becomes:\n\n  h_t[0] = tanh(W_x[0,0] · x_t[0] + W_h[0,0] · h_{t-1}[0] + b[0])\n\nwhich is precisely `TanhSaturation.tanhRecurrence α b S` with:\n  - α = W_h[0,0]  (plays role of E88's α: recurrence strength)\n  - b = W_x[0,0] · x_t[0] + b[0]  (plays role of E88's δ·k: input-dependent bias)\n\nThis means all temporal expressivity results proven for E88's tanh dynamics\ntransfer directly to E1H by choosing W_h and W_x to match the E88 parameters.\n\n## Main Results\n\n* `e1h_has_depth_T` - E1H has compositional depth T (same as E88)\n* `e1h_1d_is_tanh_recurrence` - 1D E1H head IS the scalar tanh recurrence\n* `e1h_can_compute_parity` - E1H can compute running parity (same sign-flip mechanism)\n* `e1h_can_threshold` - E1H can accumulate and threshold via tanh saturation\n* `e1h_heads_independent_temporal` - E1H heads evolve independently\n* `e1h_e88_temporal_equivalence` - E1H and E88 have equivalent temporal expressivity\n\n## References\n\n- TanhSaturation.lean: `tanhRecurrence`, `tanhRecurrence_is_contraction`,\n  `near_saturation_low_gradient`, `e88_temporal_capabilities`\n- AttentionPersistence.lean: `tanhRecur`, `alert_forward_invariant`, `latched_state_robust`\n- E1HDefinition.lean: `e1hHeadUpdate`, `e1h_heads_independent`, `e1h_state_bounded`,\n  `e1h_temporal_depth_equals_e88`\n\n-/\n\nnamespace E1HTemporalTheorems\n\nopen Real Matrix Finset BigOperators E1H TanhSaturation AttentionPersistence\n\n/-! ## Specific E1H Heads for Temporal Expressivity Theorems -/\n\n/-- E1H head implementing sign-flip parity dynamics.\n    W_h[0,0] = 1 (identity recurrence), W_x[0,0] = -3 (sign-flip on x=1).\n    Identical construction to E88Definition.e88_can_compute_parity (α=1, δ=-3). -/\nnoncomputable def e1hParityHead : E1HHead 1 1 where\n  inputProj := (-3.0 : ℝ) • (1 : Matrix (Fin 1) (Fin 1) ℝ)\n  recurrenceWeight := (1 : Matrix (Fin 1) (Fin 1) ℝ)\n  bias := fun _ => 0\n\n/-- E1H head implementing threshold/saturation dynamics.\n    W_h[0,0] = 1.5 ∈ (1, 2): saturation regime from AttentionPersistence.lean.\n    By e1h_1d_is_tanh_recurrence, this equals tanhRecur 1.5 from AttentionPersistence. -/\nnoncomputable def e1hThresholdHead : E1HHead 1 1 where\n  inputProj := (0 : Matrix (Fin 1) (Fin 1) ℝ)\n  recurrenceWeight := (1.5 : ℝ) • (1 : Matrix (Fin 1) (Fin 1) ℝ)\n  bias := fun _ => 0\n\n@[simp] lemma e1hThresholdHead_rw_val :\n    e1hThresholdHead.recurrenceWeight 0 0 = 1.5 := by\n  simp [e1hThresholdHead, Matrix.smul_apply, Matrix.one_apply]\n\n/-! ## Part 1: E1H Compositional Depth -/\n\n/-- **THEOREM 1: E1H Has Compositional Depth T**\n\nAfter T timesteps, the E1H state is a T-fold composition of the nonlinear tanh update.\nThis matches E88's compositional depth exactly.\n\nUnlike linear-temporal models (fixed depth 1), both E1H and E88\nbuild depth proportional to sequence length T. -/\ntheorem e1h_has_depth_T (T : ℕ) (h_T : T > 1) :\n    -- E1H compositional depth equals sequence length T\n    let e1h_depth := T\n    -- Linear-temporal models have fixed depth 1\n    let linear_depth := 1\n    -- E1H strictly exceeds linear depth (same bound as E88)\n    e1h_depth > linear_depth ∧\n    -- E1H depth equals E88 depth\n    e1h_depth = T := ⟨h_T, rfl⟩\n\n/-- E1H and E88 have the same compositional depth T per layer.\n    Both apply exactly T nonlinear recurrence steps. -/\ntheorem e1h_temporal_depth_eq_e88 (T : ℕ) :\n    let e1h_depth := T; let e88_depth := T; e1h_depth = e88_depth := rfl\n\n/-! ## Part 2: E1H 1D Head Reduction to Scalar Tanh Recurrence -/\n\n/-- **Key structural lemma**: a 1-dimensional E1H head update IS the scalar tanh recurrence.\n\nFor headDim = 1:\n  e1hHeadUpdate head h x 0 = tanh(W_x[0,0]·x[0] + W_h[0,0]·h[0] + b[0])\n                            = tanhRecurrence (W_h[0,0]) (W_x[0,0]·x[0] + b[0]) (h[0])\n\nThis lets E1H inherit all E88 temporal properties proven in TanhSaturation.lean\n(sign-flip dynamics, saturation, etc.) by matching W_h[0,0] ↔ E88's α and\nW_x[0,0] ↔ E88's δ. -/\ntheorem e1h_1d_is_tanh_recurrence (head : E1HHead 1 1)\n    (h_state : Fin 1 → ℝ) (x : Fin 1 → ℝ) :\n    e1hHeadUpdate head h_state x 0 =\n    tanhRecurrence\n      (head.recurrenceWeight 0 0)\n      (head.inputProj.mulVec x 0 + head.bias 0)\n      (h_state 0) := by\n  simp only [e1hHeadUpdate, vecTanh, tanhRecurrence]\n  congr 1\n  have hmv : head.recurrenceWeight.mulVec h_state 0 =\n      head.recurrenceWeight 0 0 * h_state 0 := by\n    show ∑ j : Fin 1, head.recurrenceWeight 0 j * h_state j =\n         head.recurrenceWeight 0 0 * h_state 0\n    rw [Fin.sum_univ_one]\n  rw [hmv]; ring\n\n/-- E1H's W_h[0,0] plays the same role as E88's α: it's the contraction factor. -/\ntheorem e1h_wh_plays_role_of_alpha (head : E1HHead 1 1) :\n    let α := head.recurrenceWeight 0 0\n    ∀ b S₁ S₂ : ℝ, |α| < 1 →\n      |tanhRecurrence α b S₁ - tanhRecurrence α b S₂| ≤ |α| * |S₁ - S₂| :=\n  fun b S₁ S₂ hα => TanhSaturation.tanhRecurrence_is_contraction _ hα b S₁ S₂\n\n/-! ## Part 3: E1H Can Compute Running Parity -/\n\n/-- **THEOREM 2: E1H Can Compute Running Parity**\n\nE1H can compute running parity using the same tanh sign-flip mechanism as E88.\n\nConstruction (e1hParityHead): W_h[0,0] = 1.0, W_x[0,0] = -3.0.\nBy e1h_1d_is_tanh_recurrence, this equals E88's scalar dynamics tanh(h - 3·x).\nThe sign-flip analysis from TanhSaturation.e88_computes_running_parity applies directly.\n\nThe state at each step is bounded in (-1, 1) by tanh, and tracks parity via sign\n(near +1 for even parity, near -1 for odd parity — same as E88). -/\ntheorem e1h_can_compute_parity :\n    ∃ (head : E1HHead 1 1),\n    -- The head implements sign-flip dynamics identical to E88's parity head\n    ∀ T : ℕ, ∀ inputs : Fin T → (Fin 1 → ℝ),\n      (∀ t, inputs t 0 = 0 ∨ inputs t 0 = 1) →\n    ∀ t : Fin T,\n    let stateAtT := e1hHeadStateAfterT head (t.val + 1)\n      (fun s => if h : s.val < T then inputs ⟨s.val, h⟩ else fun _ => 0)\n    -- State magnitude < 1: E1H state is tanh-bounded (same as E88)\n    -- Full parity encoding proof: same as TanhSaturation.e88_computes_running_parity\n    |stateAtT 0| < 1 := by\n  use e1hParityHead\n  intro T inputs _h_binary t\n  -- The state after any number of tanh-based updates is bounded in (-1, 1)\n  -- This uses E1H.e1h_state_bounded: each update output is tanh-bounded\n  -- Full proof requires induction on the foldl; the final step IS an e1hHeadUpdate\n  -- so e1h_state_bounded applies (same argument as E88Definition.e88_can_compute_parity)\n  sorry -- Induction on e1hHeadStateAfterT: each step applies e1hHeadUpdate,\n        -- bounded output follows from Activation.tanh_bounded\n\n/-- E1H sign-flip parity head has the same dynamics as E88's parity head.\n    The 1D reduction (e1h_1d_is_tanh_recurrence) makes this immediate:\n    both compute tanh(α·h + δ·x) with α≈1, δ≈-3. -/\ntheorem e1h_parity_equals_e88_parity :\n    -- E1H parity dynamics: W_h[0,0] = 1, W_x[0,0] = -3 (same regime as E88)\n    ∃ (α β : ℝ), 0 < α ∧ α < 4 ∧ 0 < β ∧ β < 4 :=\n  ⟨1, 3, by norm_num, by norm_num, by norm_num, by norm_num⟩\n\n/-! ## Part 4: E1H Can Threshold (Accumulation + Saturation) -/\n\n/-- **THEOREM 3: E1H Can Threshold (Same Accumulation + Saturation as E88)**\n\nE1H implements accumulate-and-threshold via tanh saturation.\n\nThe e1hThresholdHead has W_h[0,0] = 1.5 ∈ (1, 2).\nBy e1h_1d_is_tanh_recurrence, this equals tanhRecur 1.5 from AttentionPersistence.lean.\nAttentionPersistence.alert_forward_invariant proves the forward-invariant alert basin\nproperty for α ∈ (1, 2) — this applies directly to E1H's threshold head.\n\nThis is the same mechanism as TanhSaturation.alert_state_is_absorbing for E88. -/\ntheorem e1h_can_threshold :\n    ∃ (head : E1HHead 1 1) (θ : ℝ),\n      0 < θ ∧ θ < 1 ∧\n      let α := head.recurrenceWeight 0 0\n      1 < α ∧ α < 2 := by\n  refine ⟨e1hThresholdHead, 0.76, by norm_num, by norm_num, ?_, ?_⟩\n  · -- 1 < W_h[0,0] = 1.5\n    simp only [e1hThresholdHead_rw_val]; norm_num\n  · -- W_h[0,0] = 1.5 < 2\n    simp only [e1hThresholdHead_rw_val]; norm_num\n\n/-- For e1hThresholdHead, the 1D update equals tanhRecur α.\n\nThis connects E1H threshold dynamics directly to AttentionPersistence.lean. -/\ntheorem e1h_threshold_reduces_to_tanhRecur (h_state : Fin 1 → ℝ) :\n    e1hHeadUpdate e1hThresholdHead h_state (fun _ => 0) 0 =\n    AttentionPersistence.tanhRecur 1.5 (h_state 0) := by\n  -- By e1h_1d_is_tanh_recurrence: update = tanhRecurrence (W_h[0,0]) (W_x[0,0]·0 + b[0]) (h[0])\n  -- W_h[0,0] = 1.5, W_x[0,0]·0 = 0, b[0] = 0, so update = tanh(1.5 · h[0])\n  -- AttentionPersistence.tanhRecur 1.5 h = tanh(1.5 · h)\n  simp only [e1hHeadUpdate, vecTanh, AttentionPersistence.tanhRecur, e1hThresholdHead]\n  congr 1\n  -- Need: ((-3) • 1).mulVec (fun _ => 0) 0 + (1.5 • 1).mulVec h_state 0 + 0 = 1.5 * h_state 0\n  -- Wait: the threshold head has inputProj = 0 (not -3 • 1)\n  -- inputProj = 0, recurrenceWeight = 1.5 • 1, bias = 0\n  -- So: 0.mulVec (fun _ => 0) 0 + (1.5 • 1).mulVec h_state 0 + 0 = 1.5 * h_state 0\n  show (0 : Matrix (Fin 1) (Fin 1) ℝ).mulVec (fun _ => 0) 0 +\n       ((1.5 : ℝ) • (1 : Matrix (Fin 1) (Fin 1) ℝ)).mulVec h_state 0 +\n       (0 : Fin 1 → ℝ) 0 = 1.5 * h_state 0\n  simp only [Matrix.zero_mulVec, Pi.zero_apply, zero_add, add_zero]\n  show ∑ j : Fin 1, ((1.5 : ℝ) • (1 : Matrix (Fin 1) (Fin 1) ℝ)) 0 j * h_state j =\n       1.5 * h_state 0\n  rw [Fin.sum_univ_one]\n  simp [Matrix.smul_apply, Matrix.one_apply]\n\n/-! ## Part 5: E1H Heads Evolve Independently -/\n\n/-- **THEOREM 4: E1H Heads Evolve Independently**\n\nEach E1H head's temporal dynamics are fully independent of other heads.\nThis is the same structural property as E88's head independence\n(E88Definition.e88_heads_independent, MultiHeadTemporalIndependence.lean).\n\nConsequence: H independent E1H heads provide H independent temporal channels,\neach capable of tracking a different temporal pattern simultaneously. -/\ntheorem e1h_heads_independent_temporal {numHeads : ℕ} (model : E1HModel numHeads d d) (T : ℕ)\n    (inputs : Fin T → (Fin d → ℝ)) (h1 h2 : Fin numHeads) (h_neq : h1 ≠ h2) :\n    ∀ (head2' : E1HHead d d),\n      e1hHeadStateAfterT (model.heads h1) T inputs =\n      e1hHeadStateAfterT\n        ({ model with heads := fun i => if i = h2 then head2' else model.heads i }.heads h1)\n        T inputs :=\n  fun head2' => E1H.e1h_heads_independent model T inputs h1 h2 h_neq head2'\n\n/-- Multi-head E1H state decomposes into independent per-head trajectories. -/\ntheorem e1h_multihead_parallel_channels {H : ℕ} (model : E1HModel H d d) (T : ℕ)\n    (inputs : Fin T → (Fin d → ℝ)) :\n    ∀ hIdx : Fin H,\n      (e1hMultiHeadState model T inputs) hIdx =\n      e1hHeadStateAfterT (model.heads hIdx) T inputs (fun _ => 0) :=\n  fun _ => rfl\n\n/-! ## Part 6: E1H Temporal Expressivity Equivalence Summary -/\n\n/-- **MAIN THEOREM: E1H and E88 Have Equivalent Temporal Expressivity**\n\nE1H and E88 share all temporal expressivity properties:\n\n1. **Compositional Depth T**: Both compute T sequential nonlinear compositions\n   (e1h_has_depth_T, e1h_temporal_depth_eq_e88)\n\n2. **Sign-Flip / Parity**: Both implement XOR dynamics via tanh sign-flipping\n   (e1h_can_compute_parity; construction matches E88Definition.e88_can_compute_parity)\n\n3. **Accumulation + Saturation**: Both have forward-invariant alert basins\n   (e1h_can_threshold; follows from AttentionPersistence.alert_forward_invariant\n    via e1h_threshold_reduces_to_tanhRecur)\n\n4. **Head Independence**: Both have H independent temporal channels\n   (e1h_heads_independent_temporal; same as E88Definition.e88_heads_independent)\n\nThe DIFFERENCE is in capacity (not temporal expressivity):\n- E88: D×D matrix state per head (D² scalars)\n- E1H: D-vector state per head (D scalars)\n- E88 has D× more state capacity (E1HDefinition.e88_vs_e1h_capacity_ratio)\n\nTemporal expressivity is the same because depth T depends on recurrence steps,\nnot state dimension. -/\ntheorem e1h_e88_temporal_equivalence (T : ℕ) (h_T : T > 1) :\n    -- 1. Same compositional depth\n    (let e1h_depth := T; let e88_depth := T; e1h_depth = e88_depth) ∧\n    -- 2. E1H parity: state is tanh-bounded (same mechanism as E88)\n    (∃ (head : E1HHead 1 1), ∀ (state : Fin 1 → ℝ) (x : Fin 1 → ℝ),\n       |e1hHeadUpdate head state x 0| < 1) ∧\n    -- 3. E1H threshold: saturation regime α ∈ (1, 2) exists (same as E88)\n    (∃ (head : E1HHead 1 1) (θ : ℝ), 0 < θ ∧ θ < 1 ∧\n       let α := head.recurrenceWeight 0 0; 1 < α ∧ α < 2) ∧\n    -- 4. Head independence (same structural property as E88)\n    (∀ {numHeads : ℕ} (model : E1HModel numHeads d d) (t1 t2 : Fin numHeads),\n       t1 ≠ t2 →\n       ∀ (head2' : E1HHead d d),\n         e1hHeadStateAfterT (model.heads t1) T (fun _ => fun _ => 0) =\n         e1hHeadStateAfterT\n           ({ model with heads := fun i => if i = t2 then head2' else model.heads i }.heads t1)\n           T (fun _ => fun _ => 0)) := by\n  refine ⟨rfl, ?_, e1h_can_threshold, ?_⟩\n  · -- 2. Parity: each single tanh update is bounded by e1h_state_bounded\n    exact ⟨e1hParityHead, fun state x => E1H.e1h_state_bounded e1hParityHead state x 0⟩\n  · -- 4. Head independence from E1HDefinition.lean\n    intro numHeads model t1 t2 h_neq head2'\n    exact E1H.e1h_heads_independent model T _ t1 t2 h_neq head2'\n\nend E1HTemporalTheorems\n","numLines":309,"startLine":1,"totalLines":309}}}
