{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01Y7WtEEj9Lyi8bt5bjDxBRi","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→/-\n     2→Copyright (c) 2026 Elman Project. All rights reserved.\n     3→Released under Apache 2.0 license.\n     4→Authors: Elman Project Contributors\n     5→-/\n     6→import Mathlib.LinearAlgebra.Matrix.NonsingularInverse\n     7→import Mathlib.Data.Matrix.Basic\n     8→import Mathlib.Analysis.Normed.Group.Basic\n     9→import Mathlib.Topology.Basic\n    10→import ElmanProofs.Expressivity.LinearCapacity\n    11→\n    12→/-!\n    13→# Linear RNN Limitations\n    14→\n    15→This file proves that linear RNNs cannot compute certain nonlinear functions,\n    16→establishing fundamental expressivity bounds.\n    17→\n    18→## Main Results\n    19→\n    20→* `linear_output_is_linear`: Linear RNN output is a linear function of inputs\n    21→* `linear_cannot_threshold`: Linear RNNs cannot compute threshold/step functions\n    22→* `linear_cannot_xor`: Linear RNNs cannot compute XOR over history\n    23→\n    24→## Key Insight\n    25→\n    26→Since linear RNN state h_T = Σ A^{T-1-t} B x_t is a linear combination of inputs,\n    27→and output y = C h_T, the output is always a linear function of the input sequence.\n    28→This means:\n    29→1. Output is continuous in inputs\n    30→2. Output satisfies superposition: f(x + y) = f(x) + f(y), f(cx) = c f(x)\n    31→\n    32→Any function that violates these properties cannot be computed by a linear RNN.\n    33→\n    34→-/\n    35→\n    36→namespace Expressivity\n    37→\n    38→open Matrix Finset BigOperators\n    39→\n    40→variable {n m k : ℕ}\n    41→\n    42→/-! ## Linear RNN Output is Linear in Inputs -/\n    43→\n    44→/-- The weight that input at time t contributes to output component i.\n    45→    This is the (i,j) entry of C * A^{T-1-t} * B, giving how input_t[j] affects output[i]. -/\n    46→def outputWeight (C : Matrix (Fin k) (Fin n) ℝ) (A : Matrix (Fin n) (Fin n) ℝ)\n    47→    (B : Matrix (Fin n) (Fin m) ℝ) (T : ℕ) (t : Fin T) : Matrix (Fin k) (Fin m) ℝ :=\n    48→  C * (A ^ (T - 1 - t.val)) * B\n    49→\n    50→/-- Linear RNN output is a weighted sum of inputs -/\n    51→theorem linear_output_as_sum (C : Matrix (Fin k) (Fin n) ℝ) (A : Matrix (Fin n) (Fin n) ℝ)\n    52→    (B : Matrix (Fin n) (Fin m) ℝ) (T : ℕ) (inputs : Fin T → (Fin m → ℝ)) :\n    53→    C.mulVec (stateFromZero A B T inputs) =\n    54→    ∑ t : Fin T, (outputWeight C A B T t).mulVec (inputs t) := by\n    55→  rw [linear_state_is_sum]\n    56→  rw [Matrix.mulVec_sum]\n    57→  apply Finset.sum_congr rfl\n    58→  intro t _\n    59→  simp only [inputContribution, outputWeight]\n    60→  rw [Matrix.mulVec_mulVec, Matrix.mulVec_mulVec]\n    61→\n    62→/-- Linear RNN output is additive in inputs -/\n    63→theorem linear_output_additive (C : Matrix (Fin k) (Fin n) ℝ) (A : Matrix (Fin n) (Fin n) ℝ)\n    64→    (B : Matrix (Fin n) (Fin m) ℝ) (T : ℕ)\n    65→    (inputs₁ inputs₂ : Fin T → (Fin m → ℝ)) :\n    66→    C.mulVec (stateFromZero A B T (fun t => inputs₁ t + inputs₂ t)) =\n    67→    C.mulVec (stateFromZero A B T inputs₁) + C.mulVec (stateFromZero A B T inputs₂) := by\n    68→  rw [state_additive]\n    69→  exact Matrix.mulVec_add C _ _\n    70→\n    71→/-- Linear RNN output is homogeneous in inputs -/\n    72→theorem linear_output_scalar (C : Matrix (Fin k) (Fin n) ℝ) (A : Matrix (Fin n) (Fin n) ℝ)\n    73→    (B : Matrix (Fin n) (Fin m) ℝ) (T : ℕ) (c : ℝ)\n    74→    (inputs : Fin T → (Fin m → ℝ)) :\n    75→    C.mulVec (stateFromZero A B T (fun t => c • inputs t)) =\n    76→    c • C.mulVec (stateFromZero A B T inputs) := by\n    77→  rw [state_scalar]\n    78→  exact Matrix.mulVec_smul C c _\n    79→\n    80→/-! ## Threshold Functions Cannot Be Computed -/\n    81→\n    82→/-- A threshold function on scalar input sequences: outputs 1 if sum > τ, else 0 -/\n    83→noncomputable def thresholdFunction (τ : ℝ) (T : ℕ) : (Fin T → (Fin 1 → ℝ)) → (Fin 1 → ℝ) :=\n    84→  fun inputs =>\n    85→    let total := ∑ t : Fin T, inputs t 0\n    86→    fun _ => if total > τ then 1 else 0\n    87→\n    88→/-- Helper: create an input sequence with value x at position 0, zeros elsewhere -/\n    89→def singletonInput (T : ℕ) [NeZero T] (x : ℝ) : Fin T → (Fin 1 → ℝ) :=\n    90→  fun t => if t.val = 0 then fun _ => x else fun _ => 0\n    91→\n    92→/-- Sum of singleton input is just x -/\n    93→theorem singletonInput_sum (T : ℕ) [NeZero T] (x : ℝ) :\n    94→    ∑ t : Fin T, (singletonInput T x) t 0 = x := by\n    95→  rw [Fintype.sum_eq_single (0 : Fin T)]\n    96→  · simp [singletonInput]\n    97→  · intro t ht\n    98→    simp only [singletonInput]\n    99→    have : t.val ≠ 0 := by\n   100→      intro h\n   101→      have : t = 0 := Fin.ext h\n   102→      exact ht this\n   103→    simp [this]\n   104→\n   105→/-- Threshold function is not linearly computable.\n   106→    Key idea: Linear outputs are continuous, but threshold has a discontinuity at τ. -/\n   107→theorem linear_cannot_threshold (τ : ℝ) (T : ℕ) (hT : T ≥ 1) :\n   108→    ¬ LinearlyComputable (thresholdFunction τ T) := by\n   109→  have hT' : NeZero T := ⟨Nat.one_le_iff_ne_zero.mp hT⟩\n   110→  intro ⟨n, A, B, C, h_f⟩\n   111→\n   112→  -- Use linearity: singletonInput is linear in x\n   113→  have h_add : ∀ x y, singletonInput T (x + y) = singletonInput T x + singletonInput T y := by\n   114→    intro x y\n   115→    ext t j\n   116→    simp only [singletonInput, Pi.add_apply]\n   117→    split_ifs <;> ring\n   118→\n   119→  -- Get the linear output function\n   120→  let g : ℝ → ℝ := fun x => (C.mulVec (stateFromZero A B T (singletonInput T x))) 0\n   121→\n   122→  -- g is additive (by linearity of state)\n   123→  have g_add : ∀ x y, g (x + y) = g x + g y := by\n   124→    intro x y\n   125→    simp only [g]\n   126→    rw [h_add]\n   127→    have := linear_output_additive C A B T (singletonInput T x) (singletonInput T y)\n   128→    exact congrFun this 0\n   129→\n   130→  -- g is homogeneous\n   131→  have h_smul : ∀ c x, singletonInput T (c * x) = c • singletonInput T x := by\n   132→    intro c x\n   133→    ext t j\n   134→    simp only [singletonInput, Pi.smul_apply, smul_eq_mul]\n   135→    split_ifs <;> ring\n   136→\n   137→  have g_smul : ∀ c x, g (c * x) = c * g x := by\n   138→    intro c x\n   139→    simp only [g]\n   140→    rw [h_smul]\n   141→    have := linear_output_scalar C A B T c (singletonInput T x)\n   142→    exact congrFun this 0\n   143→\n   144→  -- g(0) = 0\n   145→  have g_zero : g 0 = 0 := by\n   146→    have h1 : g 0 = g (0 + 0) := by ring_nf\n   147→    have h2 : g (0 + 0) = g 0 + g 0 := g_add 0 0\n   148→    linarith [h1, h2]\n   149→\n   150→  -- g is linear: g(x) = x * g(1)\n   151→  have g_linear : ∀ x, g x = x * g 1 := by\n   152→    intro x\n   153→    have h := g_smul x 1\n   154→    simp only [mul_one] at h\n   155→    exact h\n   156→\n   157→  -- At x = τ - 1: sum = τ - 1 < τ, so threshold = 0\n   158→  have h_below : thresholdFunction τ T (singletonInput T (τ - 1)) 0 = 0 := by\n   159→    simp only [thresholdFunction, singletonInput_sum]\n   160→    split_ifs with h\n   161→    · exfalso; linarith\n   162→    · rfl\n   163→\n   164→  -- At x = τ + 1: sum = τ + 1 > τ, so threshold = 1\n   165→  have h_above : thresholdFunction τ T (singletonInput T (τ + 1)) 0 = 1 := by\n   166→    simp only [thresholdFunction, singletonInput_sum]\n   167→    split_ifs with h\n   168→    · rfl\n   169→    · exfalso; linarith\n   170→\n   171→  -- At x = τ + 2: sum = τ + 2 > τ, so threshold = 1\n   172→  have h_above2 : thresholdFunction τ T (singletonInput T (τ + 2)) 0 = 1 := by\n   173→    simp only [thresholdFunction, singletonInput_sum]\n   174→    split_ifs with h\n   175→    · rfl\n   176→    · exfalso; linarith\n   177→\n   178→  -- By h_f, g must match threshold at these points\n   179→  have eq_below := congrFun (h_f (singletonInput T (τ - 1))) 0\n   180→  have eq_above := congrFun (h_f (singletonInput T (τ + 1))) 0\n   181→  have eq_above2 := congrFun (h_f (singletonInput T (τ + 2))) 0\n   182→\n   183→  -- Substitute threshold values\n   184→  rw [h_below] at eq_below\n   185→  rw [h_above] at eq_above\n   186→  rw [h_above2] at eq_above2\n   187→\n   188→  -- eq_below: 0 = g(τ-1) = (τ-1) * g(1)\n   189→  -- eq_above: 1 = g(τ+1) = (τ+1) * g(1)\n   190→  -- eq_above2: 1 = g(τ+2) = (τ+2) * g(1)\n   191→\n   192→  -- From eq_above and eq_above2:\n   193→  -- (τ+1) * g(1) = 1 and (τ+2) * g(1) = 1\n   194→  -- Subtracting: g(1) = 0\n   195→  -- From eq_above: 0 = 1, contradiction\n   196→  have h1 : (τ + 1) * g 1 = 1 := by\n   197→    rw [← g_linear (τ + 1)]\n   198→    exact eq_above.symm\n   199→  have h2 : (τ + 2) * g 1 = 1 := by\n   200→    rw [← g_linear (τ + 2)]\n   201→    exact eq_above2.symm\n   202→  have g1_zero : g 1 = 0 := by linarith\n   203→  -- Now (τ + 1) * 0 = 1 is a contradiction\n   204→  have h_contra : (τ + 1) * g 1 = 0 := by rw [g1_zero]; ring\n   205→  linarith\n   206→\n   207→/-! ## XOR Cannot Be Computed -/\n   208→\n   209→/-- XOR of two bits represented as reals: true if exactly one is > 0.5 -/\n   210→noncomputable def xorReal (a b : ℝ) : ℝ :=\n   211→  if (a > 0.5) = (b > 0.5) then 0 else 1\n   212→\n   213→/-- For T = 2, the XOR function on binary inputs {0, 1} cannot be linear.\n   214→    XOR(0,0) = 0, XOR(0,1) = 1, XOR(1,0) = 1, XOR(1,1) = 0\n   215→    But any linear function f(x,y) = ax + by + c satisfies:\n   216→    f(0,0) + f(1,1) = f(0,1) + f(1,0)\n   217→    which gives 0 + 0 = 1 + 1, contradiction. -/\n   218→theorem xor_not_affine :\n   219→    ¬∃ (a b c : ℝ), ∀ (x y : ℝ), (x = 0 ∨ x = 1) → (y = 0 ∨ y = 1) →\n   220→      xorReal x y = a * x + b * y + c := by\n   221→  intro ⟨a, b, c, h⟩\n   222→  -- Evaluate at all four corners\n   223→  have h00 : xorReal 0 0 = a * 0 + b * 0 + c := h 0 0 (Or.inl rfl) (Or.inl rfl)\n   224→  have h01 : xorReal 0 1 = a * 0 + b * 1 + c := h 0 1 (Or.inl rfl) (Or.inr rfl)\n   225→  have h10 : xorReal 1 0 = a * 1 + b * 0 + c := h 1 0 (Or.inr rfl) (Or.inl rfl)\n   226→  have h11 : xorReal 1 1 = a * 1 + b * 1 + c := h 1 1 (Or.inr rfl) (Or.inr rfl)\n   227→  -- Compute XOR values\n   228→  have xor00 : xorReal 0 0 = 0 := by simp only [xorReal]; norm_num\n   229→  have xor01 : xorReal 0 1 = 1 := by simp only [xorReal]; norm_num\n   230→  have xor10 : xorReal 1 0 = 1 := by simp only [xorReal]; norm_num\n   231→  have xor11 : xorReal 1 1 = 0 := by simp only [xorReal]; norm_num\n   232→  -- Substitute\n   233→  rw [xor00] at h00\n   234→  rw [xor01] at h01\n   235→  rw [xor10] at h10\n   236→  rw [xor11] at h11\n   237→  simp only [mul_zero, mul_one, zero_add, add_zero] at h00 h01 h10 h11\n   238→  -- Now h00: 0 = c, h01: 1 = b + c, h10: 1 = a + c, h11: 0 = a + b + c\n   239→  -- From these: c = 0, b = 1, a = 1, but a + b + c = 2 ≠ 0\n   240→  linarith\n   241→\n   242→/-- Helper: create a 2-element input sequence from two scalar values -/\n   243→def mkInputs (x y : ℝ) : Fin 2 → (Fin 1 → ℝ) :=\n   244→  ![fun _ => x, fun _ => y]\n   245→\n   246→/-- Linear RNN output on binary inputs is an affine function.\n   247→    This follows from the linearity of state in inputs. -/\n   248→theorem linear_rnn_affine_on_binary (C : Matrix (Fin 1) (Fin n) ℝ) (A : Matrix (Fin n) (Fin n) ℝ)\n   249→    (B : Matrix (Fin n) (Fin 1) ℝ) :\n   250→    ∃ (w₀ w₁ c : ℝ),\n   251→    ∀ (x y : ℝ), (x = 0 ∨ x = 1) → (y = 0 ∨ y = 1) →\n   252→      let inputs : Fin 2 → (Fin 1 → ℝ) := mkInputs x y\n   253→      (C.mulVec (stateFromZero A B 2 inputs)) 0 = w₀ * x + w₁ * y + c := by\n   254→  -- Define the output function\n   255→  let f : ℝ → ℝ → ℝ := fun x y => (C.mulVec (stateFromZero A B 2 (mkInputs x y))) 0\n   256→  -- Key: mkInputs is linear in its arguments\n   257→  have h_mk_add : ∀ x₁ x₂ y₁ y₂,\n   258→      mkInputs (x₁ + x₂) (y₁ + y₂) = mkInputs x₁ y₁ + mkInputs x₂ y₂ := by\n   259→    intro x₁ x₂ y₁ y₂\n   260→    ext i j\n   261→    fin_cases i <;> simp [mkInputs, Matrix.cons_val_zero, Matrix.cons_val_one]\n   262→  have h_mk_smul : ∀ c x y, mkInputs (c * x) (c * y) = c • mkInputs x y := by\n   263→    intro c x y\n   264→    ext i j\n   265→    fin_cases i <;> simp [mkInputs, Matrix.cons_val_zero, Matrix.cons_val_one,\n   266→                          Pi.smul_apply, smul_eq_mul]\n   267→  -- f is additive\n   268→  have h_f_add : ∀ x₁ x₂ y₁ y₂, f (x₁ + x₂) (y₁ + y₂) = f x₁ y₁ + f x₂ y₂ := by\n   269→    intro x₁ x₂ y₁ y₂\n   270→    simp only [f]\n   271→    rw [h_mk_add]\n   272→    have := linear_output_additive C A B 2 (mkInputs x₁ y₁) (mkInputs x₂ y₂)\n   273→    exact congrFun this 0\n   274→  -- f is homogeneous\n   275→  have h_f_smul : ∀ c x y, f (c * x) (c * y) = c * f x y := by\n   276→    intro c x y\n   277→    simp only [f]\n   278→    rw [h_mk_smul]\n   279→    have := linear_output_scalar C A B 2 c (mkInputs x y)\n   280→    exact congrFun this 0\n   281→  -- Use linearity to decompose: f(x,y) = x*f(1,0) + y*f(0,1)\n   282→  use f 1 0, f 0 1, 0\n   283→  intro x y _ _\n   284→  simp only [add_zero]\n   285→  -- Show mkInputs x y = ![...] so we can work with f\n   286→  have h_mk_eq : mkInputs x y = ![fun _ => x, fun _ => y] := rfl\n   287→  -- f(x,y) = f(x,0) + f(0,y) by additivity with x₁=x, x₂=0, y₁=0, y₂=y\n   288→  have step1 : f x y = f x 0 + f 0 y := by\n   289→    have := h_f_add x 0 0 y\n   290→    simp only [add_zero, zero_add] at this\n   291→    exact this\n   292→  -- f(x,0) = x * f(1,0) by homogeneity\n   293→  have step2 : f x 0 = x * f 1 0 := by\n   294→    have := h_f_smul x 1 0\n   295→    simp only [mul_one, mul_zero] at this\n   296→    exact this\n   297→  -- f(0,y) = y * f(0,1) by homogeneity\n   298→  have step3 : f 0 y = y * f 0 1 := by\n   299→    have := h_f_smul y 0 1\n   300→    simp only [mul_zero, mul_one] at this\n   301→    exact this\n   302→  -- The goal is about mkInputs x y, which equals f x y\n   303→  -- Unfold f in the steps\n   304→  have step1' : (C.mulVec (stateFromZero A B 2 (mkInputs x y))) 0 =\n   305→                (C.mulVec (stateFromZero A B 2 (mkInputs x 0))) 0 +\n   306→                (C.mulVec (stateFromZero A B 2 (mkInputs 0 y))) 0 := step1\n   307→  have step2' : (C.mulVec (stateFromZero A B 2 (mkInputs x 0))) 0 =\n   308→                x * (C.mulVec (stateFromZero A B 2 (mkInputs 1 0))) 0 := step2\n   309→  have step3' : (C.mulVec (stateFromZero A B 2 (mkInputs 0 y))) 0 =\n   310→                y * (C.mulVec (stateFromZero A B 2 (mkInputs 0 1))) 0 := step3\n   311→  rw [step1', step2', step3']\n   312→  ring\n   313→\n   314→/-- XOR over a length-2 sequence cannot be computed by a linear RNN -/\n   315→theorem linear_cannot_xor :\n   316→    ¬ LinearlyComputable (fun inputs : Fin 2 → (Fin 1 → ℝ) =>\n   317→      fun _ : Fin 1 => xorReal (inputs 0 0) (inputs 1 0)) := by\n   318→  intro ⟨n, A, B, C, h_f⟩\n   319→  -- The linear RNN computes an affine function\n   320→  obtain ⟨w₀, w₁, c, h_affine⟩ := linear_rnn_affine_on_binary C A B\n   321→  -- But XOR is not affine\n   322→  apply xor_not_affine\n   323→  use w₀, w₁, c\n   324→  intro x y hx hy\n   325→  have h := h_f (mkInputs x y)\n   326→  have h' := h_affine x y hx hy\n   327→  -- h says: (fun _ => xorReal x y) = C.mulVec (stateFromZero A B 2 inputs)\n   328→  -- Evaluate at 0\n   329→  have h_eq : xorReal x y = (C.mulVec (stateFromZero A B 2 (mkInputs x y))) 0 := by\n   330→    have := congrFun h 0\n   331→    simp only [mkInputs, Matrix.cons_val_zero, Matrix.cons_val_one] at this\n   332→    exact this\n   333→  rw [h_eq]\n   334→  -- h' gives us the affine form\n   335→  simp only [mkInputs] at h'\n   336→  exact h'\n   337→\n   338→end Expressivity\n   339→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"95379173-9fa9-4c3b-b84e-0caa1677a98b","uuid":"e47d9312-7640-48ae-9da6-e340d4c056d2","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/home/erikg/elman-proofs/ElmanProofs/Expressivity/LinearLimitations.lean","content":"/-\nCopyright (c) 2026 Elman Project. All rights reserved.\nReleased under Apache 2.0 license.\nAuthors: Elman Project Contributors\n-/\nimport Mathlib.LinearAlgebra.Matrix.NonsingularInverse\nimport Mathlib.Data.Matrix.Basic\nimport Mathlib.Analysis.Normed.Group.Basic\nimport Mathlib.Topology.Basic\nimport ElmanProofs.Expressivity.LinearCapacity\n\n/-!\n# Linear RNN Limitations\n\nThis file proves that linear RNNs cannot compute certain nonlinear functions,\nestablishing fundamental expressivity bounds.\n\n## Main Results\n\n* `linear_output_is_linear`: Linear RNN output is a linear function of inputs\n* `linear_cannot_threshold`: Linear RNNs cannot compute threshold/step functions\n* `linear_cannot_xor`: Linear RNNs cannot compute XOR over history\n\n## Key Insight\n\nSince linear RNN state h_T = Σ A^{T-1-t} B x_t is a linear combination of inputs,\nand output y = C h_T, the output is always a linear function of the input sequence.\nThis means:\n1. Output is continuous in inputs\n2. Output satisfies superposition: f(x + y) = f(x) + f(y), f(cx) = c f(x)\n\nAny function that violates these properties cannot be computed by a linear RNN.\n\n-/\n\nnamespace Expressivity\n\nopen Matrix Finset BigOperators\n\nvariable {n m k : ℕ}\n\n/-! ## Linear RNN Output is Linear in Inputs -/\n\n/-- The weight that input at time t contributes to output component i.\n    This is the (i,j) entry of C * A^{T-1-t} * B, giving how input_t[j] affects output[i]. -/\ndef outputWeight (C : Matrix (Fin k) (Fin n) ℝ) (A : Matrix (Fin n) (Fin n) ℝ)\n    (B : Matrix (Fin n) (Fin m) ℝ) (T : ℕ) (t : Fin T) : Matrix (Fin k) (Fin m) ℝ :=\n  C * (A ^ (T - 1 - t.val)) * B\n\n/-- Linear RNN output is a weighted sum of inputs -/\ntheorem linear_output_as_sum (C : Matrix (Fin k) (Fin n) ℝ) (A : Matrix (Fin n) (Fin n) ℝ)\n    (B : Matrix (Fin n) (Fin m) ℝ) (T : ℕ) (inputs : Fin T → (Fin m → ℝ)) :\n    C.mulVec (stateFromZero A B T inputs) =\n    ∑ t : Fin T, (outputWeight C A B T t).mulVec (inputs t) := by\n  rw [linear_state_is_sum]\n  rw [Matrix.mulVec_sum]\n  apply Finset.sum_congr rfl\n  intro t _\n  simp only [inputContribution, outputWeight]\n  rw [Matrix.mulVec_mulVec, Matrix.mulVec_mulVec]\n\n/-- Linear RNN output is additive in inputs -/\ntheorem linear_output_additive (C : Matrix (Fin k) (Fin n) ℝ) (A : Matrix (Fin n) (Fin n) ℝ)\n    (B : Matrix (Fin n) (Fin m) ℝ) (T : ℕ)\n    (inputs₁ inputs₂ : Fin T → (Fin m → ℝ)) :\n    C.mulVec (stateFromZero A B T (fun t => inputs₁ t + inputs₂ t)) =\n    C.mulVec (stateFromZero A B T inputs₁) + C.mulVec (stateFromZero A B T inputs₂) := by\n  rw [state_additive]\n  exact Matrix.mulVec_add C _ _\n\n/-- Linear RNN output is homogeneous in inputs -/\ntheorem linear_output_scalar (C : Matrix (Fin k) (Fin n) ℝ) (A : Matrix (Fin n) (Fin n) ℝ)\n    (B : Matrix (Fin n) (Fin m) ℝ) (T : ℕ) (c : ℝ)\n    (inputs : Fin T → (Fin m → ℝ)) :\n    C.mulVec (stateFromZero A B T (fun t => c • inputs t)) =\n    c • C.mulVec (stateFromZero A B T inputs) := by\n  rw [state_scalar]\n  exact Matrix.mulVec_smul C c _\n\n/-! ## Threshold Functions Cannot Be Computed -/\n\n/-- A threshold function on scalar input sequences: outputs 1 if sum > τ, else 0 -/\nnoncomputable def thresholdFunction (τ : ℝ) (T : ℕ) : (Fin T → (Fin 1 → ℝ)) → (Fin 1 → ℝ) :=\n  fun inputs =>\n    let total := ∑ t : Fin T, inputs t 0\n    fun _ => if total > τ then 1 else 0\n\n/-- Helper: create an input sequence with value x at position 0, zeros elsewhere -/\ndef singletonInput (T : ℕ) [NeZero T] (x : ℝ) : Fin T → (Fin 1 → ℝ) :=\n  fun t => if t.val = 0 then fun _ => x else fun _ => 0\n\n/-- Sum of singleton input is just x -/\ntheorem singletonInput_sum (T : ℕ) [NeZero T] (x : ℝ) :\n    ∑ t : Fin T, (singletonInput T x) t 0 = x := by\n  rw [Fintype.sum_eq_single (0 : Fin T)]\n  · simp [singletonInput]\n  · intro t ht\n    simp only [singletonInput]\n    have : t.val ≠ 0 := by\n      intro h\n      have : t = 0 := Fin.ext h\n      exact ht this\n    simp [this]\n\n/-- Threshold function is not linearly computable.\n    Key idea: Linear outputs are continuous, but threshold has a discontinuity at τ. -/\ntheorem linear_cannot_threshold (τ : ℝ) (T : ℕ) (hT : T ≥ 1) :\n    ¬ LinearlyComputable (thresholdFunction τ T) := by\n  have hT' : NeZero T := ⟨Nat.one_le_iff_ne_zero.mp hT⟩\n  intro ⟨n, A, B, C, h_f⟩\n\n  -- Use linearity: singletonInput is linear in x\n  have h_add : ∀ x y, singletonInput T (x + y) = singletonInput T x + singletonInput T y := by\n    intro x y\n    ext t j\n    simp only [singletonInput, Pi.add_apply]\n    split_ifs <;> ring\n\n  -- Get the linear output function\n  let g : ℝ → ℝ := fun x => (C.mulVec (stateFromZero A B T (singletonInput T x))) 0\n\n  -- g is additive (by linearity of state)\n  have g_add : ∀ x y, g (x + y) = g x + g y := by\n    intro x y\n    simp only [g]\n    rw [h_add]\n    have := linear_output_additive C A B T (singletonInput T x) (singletonInput T y)\n    exact congrFun this 0\n\n  -- g is homogeneous\n  have h_smul : ∀ c x, singletonInput T (c * x) = c • singletonInput T x := by\n    intro c x\n    ext t j\n    simp only [singletonInput, Pi.smul_apply, smul_eq_mul]\n    split_ifs <;> ring\n\n  have g_smul : ∀ c x, g (c * x) = c * g x := by\n    intro c x\n    simp only [g]\n    rw [h_smul]\n    have := linear_output_scalar C A B T c (singletonInput T x)\n    exact congrFun this 0\n\n  -- g(0) = 0\n  have g_zero : g 0 = 0 := by\n    have h1 : g 0 = g (0 + 0) := by ring_nf\n    have h2 : g (0 + 0) = g 0 + g 0 := g_add 0 0\n    linarith [h1, h2]\n\n  -- g is linear: g(x) = x * g(1)\n  have g_linear : ∀ x, g x = x * g 1 := by\n    intro x\n    have h := g_smul x 1\n    simp only [mul_one] at h\n    exact h\n\n  -- At x = τ - 1: sum = τ - 1 < τ, so threshold = 0\n  have h_below : thresholdFunction τ T (singletonInput T (τ - 1)) 0 = 0 := by\n    simp only [thresholdFunction, singletonInput_sum]\n    split_ifs with h\n    · exfalso; linarith\n    · rfl\n\n  -- At x = τ + 1: sum = τ + 1 > τ, so threshold = 1\n  have h_above : thresholdFunction τ T (singletonInput T (τ + 1)) 0 = 1 := by\n    simp only [thresholdFunction, singletonInput_sum]\n    split_ifs with h\n    · rfl\n    · exfalso; linarith\n\n  -- At x = τ + 2: sum = τ + 2 > τ, so threshold = 1\n  have h_above2 : thresholdFunction τ T (singletonInput T (τ + 2)) 0 = 1 := by\n    simp only [thresholdFunction, singletonInput_sum]\n    split_ifs with h\n    · rfl\n    · exfalso; linarith\n\n  -- By h_f, g must match threshold at these points\n  have eq_below := congrFun (h_f (singletonInput T (τ - 1))) 0\n  have eq_above := congrFun (h_f (singletonInput T (τ + 1))) 0\n  have eq_above2 := congrFun (h_f (singletonInput T (τ + 2))) 0\n\n  -- Substitute threshold values\n  rw [h_below] at eq_below\n  rw [h_above] at eq_above\n  rw [h_above2] at eq_above2\n\n  -- eq_below: 0 = g(τ-1) = (τ-1) * g(1)\n  -- eq_above: 1 = g(τ+1) = (τ+1) * g(1)\n  -- eq_above2: 1 = g(τ+2) = (τ+2) * g(1)\n\n  -- From eq_above and eq_above2:\n  -- (τ+1) * g(1) = 1 and (τ+2) * g(1) = 1\n  -- Subtracting: g(1) = 0\n  -- From eq_above: 0 = 1, contradiction\n  have h1 : (τ + 1) * g 1 = 1 := by\n    rw [← g_linear (τ + 1)]\n    exact eq_above.symm\n  have h2 : (τ + 2) * g 1 = 1 := by\n    rw [← g_linear (τ + 2)]\n    exact eq_above2.symm\n  have g1_zero : g 1 = 0 := by linarith\n  -- Now (τ + 1) * 0 = 1 is a contradiction\n  have h_contra : (τ + 1) * g 1 = 0 := by rw [g1_zero]; ring\n  linarith\n\n/-! ## XOR Cannot Be Computed -/\n\n/-- XOR of two bits represented as reals: true if exactly one is > 0.5 -/\nnoncomputable def xorReal (a b : ℝ) : ℝ :=\n  if (a > 0.5) = (b > 0.5) then 0 else 1\n\n/-- For T = 2, the XOR function on binary inputs {0, 1} cannot be linear.\n    XOR(0,0) = 0, XOR(0,1) = 1, XOR(1,0) = 1, XOR(1,1) = 0\n    But any linear function f(x,y) = ax + by + c satisfies:\n    f(0,0) + f(1,1) = f(0,1) + f(1,0)\n    which gives 0 + 0 = 1 + 1, contradiction. -/\ntheorem xor_not_affine :\n    ¬∃ (a b c : ℝ), ∀ (x y : ℝ), (x = 0 ∨ x = 1) → (y = 0 ∨ y = 1) →\n      xorReal x y = a * x + b * y + c := by\n  intro ⟨a, b, c, h⟩\n  -- Evaluate at all four corners\n  have h00 : xorReal 0 0 = a * 0 + b * 0 + c := h 0 0 (Or.inl rfl) (Or.inl rfl)\n  have h01 : xorReal 0 1 = a * 0 + b * 1 + c := h 0 1 (Or.inl rfl) (Or.inr rfl)\n  have h10 : xorReal 1 0 = a * 1 + b * 0 + c := h 1 0 (Or.inr rfl) (Or.inl rfl)\n  have h11 : xorReal 1 1 = a * 1 + b * 1 + c := h 1 1 (Or.inr rfl) (Or.inr rfl)\n  -- Compute XOR values\n  have xor00 : xorReal 0 0 = 0 := by simp only [xorReal]; norm_num\n  have xor01 : xorReal 0 1 = 1 := by simp only [xorReal]; norm_num\n  have xor10 : xorReal 1 0 = 1 := by simp only [xorReal]; norm_num\n  have xor11 : xorReal 1 1 = 0 := by simp only [xorReal]; norm_num\n  -- Substitute\n  rw [xor00] at h00\n  rw [xor01] at h01\n  rw [xor10] at h10\n  rw [xor11] at h11\n  simp only [mul_zero, mul_one, zero_add, add_zero] at h00 h01 h10 h11\n  -- Now h00: 0 = c, h01: 1 = b + c, h10: 1 = a + c, h11: 0 = a + b + c\n  -- From these: c = 0, b = 1, a = 1, but a + b + c = 2 ≠ 0\n  linarith\n\n/-- Helper: create a 2-element input sequence from two scalar values -/\ndef mkInputs (x y : ℝ) : Fin 2 → (Fin 1 → ℝ) :=\n  ![fun _ => x, fun _ => y]\n\n/-- Linear RNN output on binary inputs is an affine function.\n    This follows from the linearity of state in inputs. -/\ntheorem linear_rnn_affine_on_binary (C : Matrix (Fin 1) (Fin n) ℝ) (A : Matrix (Fin n) (Fin n) ℝ)\n    (B : Matrix (Fin n) (Fin 1) ℝ) :\n    ∃ (w₀ w₁ c : ℝ),\n    ∀ (x y : ℝ), (x = 0 ∨ x = 1) → (y = 0 ∨ y = 1) →\n      let inputs : Fin 2 → (Fin 1 → ℝ) := mkInputs x y\n      (C.mulVec (stateFromZero A B 2 inputs)) 0 = w₀ * x + w₁ * y + c := by\n  -- Define the output function\n  let f : ℝ → ℝ → ℝ := fun x y => (C.mulVec (stateFromZero A B 2 (mkInputs x y))) 0\n  -- Key: mkInputs is linear in its arguments\n  have h_mk_add : ∀ x₁ x₂ y₁ y₂,\n      mkInputs (x₁ + x₂) (y₁ + y₂) = mkInputs x₁ y₁ + mkInputs x₂ y₂ := by\n    intro x₁ x₂ y₁ y₂\n    ext i j\n    fin_cases i <;> simp [mkInputs, Matrix.cons_val_zero, Matrix.cons_val_one]\n  have h_mk_smul : ∀ c x y, mkInputs (c * x) (c * y) = c • mkInputs x y := by\n    intro c x y\n    ext i j\n    fin_cases i <;> simp [mkInputs, Matrix.cons_val_zero, Matrix.cons_val_one,\n                          Pi.smul_apply, smul_eq_mul]\n  -- f is additive\n  have h_f_add : ∀ x₁ x₂ y₁ y₂, f (x₁ + x₂) (y₁ + y₂) = f x₁ y₁ + f x₂ y₂ := by\n    intro x₁ x₂ y₁ y₂\n    simp only [f]\n    rw [h_mk_add]\n    have := linear_output_additive C A B 2 (mkInputs x₁ y₁) (mkInputs x₂ y₂)\n    exact congrFun this 0\n  -- f is homogeneous\n  have h_f_smul : ∀ c x y, f (c * x) (c * y) = c * f x y := by\n    intro c x y\n    simp only [f]\n    rw [h_mk_smul]\n    have := linear_output_scalar C A B 2 c (mkInputs x y)\n    exact congrFun this 0\n  -- Use linearity to decompose: f(x,y) = x*f(1,0) + y*f(0,1)\n  use f 1 0, f 0 1, 0\n  intro x y _ _\n  simp only [add_zero]\n  -- Show mkInputs x y = ![...] so we can work with f\n  have h_mk_eq : mkInputs x y = ![fun _ => x, fun _ => y] := rfl\n  -- f(x,y) = f(x,0) + f(0,y) by additivity with x₁=x, x₂=0, y₁=0, y₂=y\n  have step1 : f x y = f x 0 + f 0 y := by\n    have := h_f_add x 0 0 y\n    simp only [add_zero, zero_add] at this\n    exact this\n  -- f(x,0) = x * f(1,0) by homogeneity\n  have step2 : f x 0 = x * f 1 0 := by\n    have := h_f_smul x 1 0\n    simp only [mul_one, mul_zero] at this\n    exact this\n  -- f(0,y) = y * f(0,1) by homogeneity\n  have step3 : f 0 y = y * f 0 1 := by\n    have := h_f_smul y 0 1\n    simp only [mul_zero, mul_one] at this\n    exact this\n  -- The goal is about mkInputs x y, which equals f x y\n  -- Unfold f in the steps\n  have step1' : (C.mulVec (stateFromZero A B 2 (mkInputs x y))) 0 =\n                (C.mulVec (stateFromZero A B 2 (mkInputs x 0))) 0 +\n                (C.mulVec (stateFromZero A B 2 (mkInputs 0 y))) 0 := step1\n  have step2' : (C.mulVec (stateFromZero A B 2 (mkInputs x 0))) 0 =\n                x * (C.mulVec (stateFromZero A B 2 (mkInputs 1 0))) 0 := step2\n  have step3' : (C.mulVec (stateFromZero A B 2 (mkInputs 0 y))) 0 =\n                y * (C.mulVec (stateFromZero A B 2 (mkInputs 0 1))) 0 := step3\n  rw [step1', step2', step3']\n  ring\n\n/-- XOR over a length-2 sequence cannot be computed by a linear RNN -/\ntheorem linear_cannot_xor :\n    ¬ LinearlyComputable (fun inputs : Fin 2 → (Fin 1 → ℝ) =>\n      fun _ : Fin 1 => xorReal (inputs 0 0) (inputs 1 0)) := by\n  intro ⟨n, A, B, C, h_f⟩\n  -- The linear RNN computes an affine function\n  obtain ⟨w₀, w₁, c, h_affine⟩ := linear_rnn_affine_on_binary C A B\n  -- But XOR is not affine\n  apply xor_not_affine\n  use w₀, w₁, c\n  intro x y hx hy\n  have h := h_f (mkInputs x y)\n  have h' := h_affine x y hx hy\n  -- h says: (fun _ => xorReal x y) = C.mulVec (stateFromZero A B 2 inputs)\n  -- Evaluate at 0\n  have h_eq : xorReal x y = (C.mulVec (stateFromZero A B 2 (mkInputs x y))) 0 := by\n    have := congrFun h 0\n    simp only [mkInputs, Matrix.cons_val_zero, Matrix.cons_val_one] at this\n    exact this\n  rw [h_eq]\n  -- h' gives us the affine form\n  simp only [mkInputs] at h'\n  exact h'\n\nend Expressivity\n","numLines":339,"startLine":1,"totalLines":339}}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01Gsd6ppWpoAzc7zkgoT7aNM","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_011bWZJCpDRyzZypMw3hKY6w","name":"Read","input":{"file_path":"/home/erikg/elman-proofs/ElmanProofs/Expressivity/E1HDefinition.lean"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":13867,"cache_read_input_tokens":28884,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":13867},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"95379173-9fa9-4c3b-b84e-0caa1677a98b","uuid":"0b230961-ee8c-4caa-bbe5-cc348b09bbc1"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_011bWZJCpDRyzZypMw3hKY6w","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→/-\n     2→Copyright (c) 2026 Elman Project. All rights reserved.\n     3→Released under Apache 2.0 license.\n     4→Authors: Elman Project Contributors\n     5→-/\n     6→import Mathlib.LinearAlgebra.Matrix.NonsingularInverse\n     7→import Mathlib.Data.Matrix.Basic\n     8→import Mathlib.Analysis.Normed.Group.Basic\n     9→import Mathlib.Analysis.SpecialFunctions.Trigonometric.Basic\n    10→import Mathlib.Analysis.SpecialFunctions.ExpDeriv\n    11→import Mathlib.Topology.Basic\n    12→import ElmanProofs.Activations.Lipschitz\n    13→\n    14→/-!\n    15→# E1H: Multi-Head Elman (Vector State)\n    16→\n    17→This file provides the SINGLE SOURCE OF TRUTH for E1H architecture formalization.\n    18→\n    19→## E1H Architecture\n    20→\n    21→E1H is a multi-head Elman recurrent network with:\n    22→1. **Multi-head vector states**: H heads, each with a vector state of dimension D\n    23→2. **Elman temporal dynamics**: h_t = tanh(W_x·x_t + W_h·h_{t-1} + b)\n    24→3. **Independent head evolution**: Each head runs autonomous temporal dynamics\n    25→4. **No decay factor**: Unlike E88, there is no separate α decay scalar\n    26→5. **No outer product**: Unlike E88, the state update is not an outer product operation\n    27→\n    28→## Core Update Rule\n    29→\n    30→For each head h:\n    31→```\n    32→h_t^h = tanh(W_x^h · x_t + W_h^h · h_{t-1}^h + b^h)\n    33→```\n    34→\n    35→Where:\n    36→- h ∈ ℝ^D: Vector hidden state for head h (NOT a D×D matrix like E88)\n    37→- W_x ∈ ℝ^{D×inputDim}: Input projection matrix\n    38→- W_h ∈ ℝ^{D×D}: Recurrence (state-to-state) weight matrix\n    39→- b ∈ ℝ^D: Bias vector\n    40→- tanh: Applied element-wise to the resulting vector\n    41→\n    42→## Key Differences from E88\n    43→\n    44→| Property        | E88                      | E1H                           |\n    45→|-----------------|--------------------------|-------------------------------|\n    46→| State shape     | D×D matrix per head      | D-vector per head             |\n    47→| State dimension | D² scalars per head      | D scalars per head            |\n    48→| Update          | tanh(α·S + δ·outer(v,k)) | tanh(W_x·x + W_h·h + b)      |\n    49→| Decay factor    | α ∈ (0, 2)               | None (folded into W_h)        |\n    50→| Input coupling  | Outer product (rank-1)   | Full matrix-vector product    |\n    51→| Parameters      | K_h, V_h + scalars       | W_x_h, W_h_h, b_h             |\n    52→\n    53→## Key Properties\n    54→\n    55→1. **Shared Temporal Depth**: Both E1H and E88 have compositional depth T per layer\n    56→2. **Vector vs Matrix Capacity**: E88 state has D² entries vs E1H's D entries per head\n    57→3. **Head Independence**: Each head evolves independently (like E88)\n    58→4. **Tanh Boundedness**: h_t ∈ [-1, 1]^D at all times\n    59→\n    60→## Main Results\n    61→\n    62→* `e1hHeadUpdate` - Core per-head update function\n    63→* `e1hHeadStateAfterT` - Single-head state after T steps\n    64→* `e1hMultiHeadState` - Multi-head state evolution\n    65→* `e1h_heads_independent` - Heads evolve independently\n    66→* `e1h_state_bounded` - States are bounded in [-1, 1]^D\n    67→* `e1h_temporal_depth` - E1H has compositional depth T (same as E88)\n    68→* `e1h_vector_state_dimension` - E1H state has D scalars per head (vs D² for E88)\n    69→\n    70→-/\n    71→\n    72→namespace E1H\n    73→\n    74→open Real Matrix Finset BigOperators\n    75→\n    76→/-! ## Part 1: E1H Core Architecture -/\n    77→\n    78→/-- E1H single-head configuration.\n    79→    Each head maintains a D-dimensional vector state (not a matrix like E88). -/\n    80→structure E1HHead (inputDim headDim : ℕ) where\n    81→  /-- Input projection matrix W_x: headDim × inputDim -/\n    82→  inputProj : Matrix (Fin headDim) (Fin inputDim) ℝ\n    83→  /-- Recurrence weight matrix W_h: headDim × headDim -/\n    84→  recurrenceWeight : Matrix (Fin headDim) (Fin headDim) ℝ\n    85→  /-- Bias vector b: headDim -/\n    86→  bias : Fin headDim → ℝ\n    87→\n    88→/-- E1H multi-head model.\n    89→    H independent Elman RNN heads with shared input via a single in-projection. -/\n    90→structure E1HModel (numHeads inputDim headDim : ℕ) where\n    91→  /-- Configuration for each head -/\n    92→  heads : Fin numHeads → E1HHead inputDim headDim\n    93→  /-- Output projection from all head states concatenated -/\n    94→  outputProj : Matrix (Fin inputDim) (Fin (numHeads * headDim)) ℝ\n    95→\n    96→/-- Vector hidden state for a single E1H head.\n    97→    This is a D-dimensional vector, NOT a D×D matrix like E88's HeadState. -/\n    98→abbrev E1HHeadState (headDim : ℕ) := Fin headDim → ℝ\n    99→\n   100→/-- E1H state for all heads: a vector state per head. -/\n   101→abbrev E1HState (numHeads headDim : ℕ) := Fin numHeads → E1HHeadState headDim\n   102→\n   103→/-! ## Part 2: E1H State Update Dynamics -/\n   104→\n   105→/-- Element-wise tanh applied to a vector -/\n   106→noncomputable def vecTanh {n : ℕ} (v : Fin n → ℝ) : Fin n → ℝ :=\n   107→  fun i => tanh (v i)\n   108→\n   109→/-- Single-head E1H state update: h' = tanh(W_x·x + W_h·h + b)\n   110→    This is the standard Elman recurrence with full matrix projections.\n   111→    Contrast with E88 which uses outer products and a scalar decay. -/\n   112→noncomputable def e1hHeadUpdate (head : E1HHead d d) (state : E1HHeadState d)\n   113→    (input : Fin d → ℝ) : E1HHeadState d :=\n   114→  let wx_x := head.inputProj.mulVec input          -- W_x · x_t\n   115→  let wh_h := head.recurrenceWeight.mulVec state    -- W_h · h_{t-1}\n   116→  let preActivation := fun i => wx_x i + wh_h i + head.bias i\n   117→  vecTanh preActivation\n   118→\n   119→/-- E1H state after T timesteps for a single head -/\n   120→noncomputable def e1hHeadStateAfterT (head : E1HHead d d) (T : ℕ)\n   121→    (inputs : Fin T → (Fin d → ℝ)) (initState : E1HHeadState d := fun _ => 0) :\n   122→    E1HHeadState d :=\n   123→  List.foldl (fun s x => e1hHeadUpdate head s x) initState (List.ofFn inputs)\n   124→\n   125→/-- Multi-head E1H state evolution.\n   126→    Each head evolves independently — same structural property as E88. -/\n   127→noncomputable def e1hMultiHeadState {h : ℕ} (model : E1HModel h d d) (T : ℕ)\n   128→    (inputs : Fin T → (Fin d → ℝ)) (initState : E1HState h d := fun _ => fun _ => 0) :\n   129→    E1HState h d :=\n   130→  fun head_idx => e1hHeadStateAfterT (model.heads head_idx) T inputs (initState head_idx)\n   131→\n   132→/-! ## Part 3: Boundedness of E1H States -/\n   133→\n   134→/-- E1H state elements are bounded in (-1, 1) after each update.\n   135→    This follows immediately from the tanh nonlinearity. -/\n   136→theorem e1h_state_bounded (head : E1HHead d d) (state : E1HHeadState d)\n   137→    (input : Fin d → ℝ) :\n   138→    ∀ i : Fin d, |e1hHeadUpdate head state input i| < 1 := by\n   139→  intro i\n   140→  simp only [e1hHeadUpdate, vecTanh]\n   141→  exact Activation.tanh_bounded _\n   142→\n   143→/-- E1H state elements are in the open interval (-1, 1) -/\n   144→theorem e1h_state_in_unit_interval (head : E1HHead d d) (state : E1HHeadState d)\n   145→    (input : Fin d → ℝ) :\n   146→    ∀ i : Fin d, -1 < e1hHeadUpdate head state input i ∧\n   147→                 e1hHeadUpdate head state input i < 1 := by\n   148→  intro i\n   149→  simp only [e1hHeadUpdate, vecTanh]\n   150→  have hb := Activation.tanh_bounded (head.inputProj.mulVec input i +\n   151→                                       head.recurrenceWeight.mulVec state i +\n   152→                                       head.bias i)\n   153→  exact abs_lt.mp hb\n   154→\n   155→/-! ## Part 4: Head Independence -/\n   156→\n   157→/-- **E1H Heads Evolve Independently**\n   158→\n   159→Each head's state update depends only on:\n   160→1. Its own previous state h^k_{t-1}\n   161→2. The current input x_t (through its own W_x^k, W_h^k, b^k parameters)\n   162→\n   163→There is NO cross-head communication in the state dynamics. -/\n   164→theorem e1h_heads_independent {h : ℕ} (model : E1HModel h d d) (T : ℕ)\n   165→    (inputs : Fin T → (Fin d → ℝ)) (h1 h2 : Fin h) (h_neq : h1 ≠ h2)\n   166→    (head2' : E1HHead d d) :\n   167→    -- The state of head h1 is unaffected when head h2's parameters are replaced\n   168→    e1hHeadStateAfterT (model.heads h1) T inputs =\n   169→    e1hHeadStateAfterT\n   170→      ({ model with heads := fun i => if i = h2 then head2' else model.heads i }.heads h1)\n   171→      T inputs := by\n   172→  simp only [if_neg h_neq]\n   173→\n   174→/-- Heads can be computed in parallel (no sequential dependency between heads) -/\n   175→theorem e1h_heads_parallel_computable {h : ℕ} (model : E1HModel h d d) (T : ℕ)\n   176→    (inputs : Fin T → (Fin d → ℝ)) :\n   177→    ∀ h1 h2 : Fin h, h1 ≠ h2 →\n   178→      let state := e1hMultiHeadState model T inputs\n   179→      state h1 = e1hHeadStateAfterT (model.heads h1) T inputs (fun _ => 0) ∧\n   180→      state h2 = e1hHeadStateAfterT (model.heads h2) T inputs (fun _ => 0) := by\n   181→  intro h1 h2 _\n   182→  exact ⟨rfl, rfl⟩\n   183→\n   184→/-! ## Part 5: Temporal Depth -/\n   185→\n   186→/-- E1H has compositional depth T per layer (same as E88).\n   187→\n   188→The state at time T is computed by T sequential applications of the nonlinear\n   189→update function. The compositional depth grows with sequence length, identical\n   190→to E88 and unlike linear-temporal models (which have fixed depth 1). -/\n   191→theorem e1h_temporal_depth (T : ℕ) (h_T : T > 1) :\n   192→    -- E1H compositional depth equals sequence length\n   193→    let e1h_depth := T\n   194→    -- Linear-temporal models have fixed depth 1\n   195→    let linear_depth := 1\n   196→    e1h_depth > linear_depth := h_T\n   197→\n   198→/-- E1H compositional depth equals E88 compositional depth.\n   199→    Both architectures produce T sequential nonlinear applications per layer. -/\n   200→theorem e1h_temporal_depth_equals_e88 (T : ℕ) :\n   201→    -- Both E1H and E88 have depth T\n   202→    let e1h_depth := T\n   203→    let e88_depth := T\n   204→    e1h_depth = e88_depth := rfl\n   205→\n   206→/-! ## Part 6: State Dimension Comparison -/\n   207→\n   208→/-- E1H state dimension per head: D scalars (a vector).\n   209→\n   210→This is the KEY structural difference from E88. -/\n   211→def e1hStateScalarsPerHead (headDim : ℕ) : ℕ := headDim\n   212→\n   213→/-- E88 state dimension per head: D × D scalars (a matrix). -/\n   214→def e88StateScalarsPerHead (headDim : ℕ) : ℕ := headDim * headDim\n   215→\n   216→/-- **E88 has strictly more state capacity than E1H** (when headDim ≥ 2).\n   217→\n   218→For headDim ≥ 2, E88's D×D matrix state contains strictly more scalar\n   219→parameters than E1H's D-vector state.\n   220→\n   221→This is the formal statement that motivates:\n   222→- e88-exceeds-e1h-capacity: Prove E88 matrix state strictly exceeds E1H vector state -/\n   223→theorem e88_state_exceeds_e1h_state (headDim : ℕ) (h : headDim ≥ 2) :\n   224→    e1hStateScalarsPerHead headDim < e88StateScalarsPerHead headDim := by\n   225→  simp only [e1hStateScalarsPerHead, e88StateScalarsPerHead]\n   226→  -- headDim < headDim * headDim when headDim ≥ 2\n   227→  nlinarith [Nat.mul_pos (by omega : 0 < headDim) (by omega : 0 < headDim)]\n   228→\n   229→/-- E88 state advantage factor: D times more capacity per head -/\n   230→theorem e88_vs_e1h_capacity_ratio (headDim : ℕ) :\n   231→    e88StateScalarsPerHead headDim = headDim * e1hStateScalarsPerHead headDim := by\n   232→  simp only [e88StateScalarsPerHead, e1hStateScalarsPerHead]\n   233→\n   234→/-! ## Part 7: Total State Comparison -/\n   235→\n   236→/-- Total E1H state scalars across all heads: numHeads × headDim -/\n   237→def e1hTotalState (numHeads headDim : ℕ) : ℕ := numHeads * headDim\n   238→\n   239→/-- Total E88 state scalars across all heads: numHeads × headDim × headDim -/\n   240→def e88TotalState (numHeads headDim : ℕ) : ℕ := numHeads * headDim * headDim\n   241→\n   242→/-- E88 total state exceeds E1H total state when headDim ≥ 2 -/\n   243→theorem e88_total_state_exceeds_e1h (numHeads headDim : ℕ)\n   244→    (hH : numHeads ≥ 1) (hD : headDim ≥ 2) :\n   245→    e1hTotalState numHeads headDim < e88TotalState numHeads headDim := by\n   246→  simp only [e1hTotalState, e88TotalState]\n   247→  have hd1 : 1 < headDim := by omega\n   248→  have hn1 : 0 < numHeads := by omega\n   249→  nlinarith [Nat.mul_lt_mul_of_pos_left (by nlinarith : headDim < headDim * headDim) hn1]\n   250→\n   251→/-! ## Part 8: Relationship to E88 -/\n   252→\n   253→/-- **E1H and E88 share the same temporal structure**.\n   254→\n   255→Both architectures:\n   256→1. Apply H independent heads\n   257→2. Each head runs T sequential nonlinear recurrence steps\n   258→3. No cross-head state communication\n   259→\n   260→The key difference is the state SHAPE: E1H has vector state (D), E88 has matrix state (D×D). -/\n   261→theorem e1h_e88_shared_temporal_structure (T : ℕ) (headDim : ℕ) :\n   262→    -- Both have temporal depth T\n   263→    T = T ∧\n   264→    -- E88 has headDim times more state per head\n   265→    e88StateScalarsPerHead headDim = headDim * e1hStateScalarsPerHead headDim :=\n   266→  ⟨rfl, by simp [e88StateScalarsPerHead, e1hStateScalarsPerHead]⟩\n   267→\n   268→/-! ## Appendix: Architecture Comparison Summary\n   269→\n   270→```\n   271→                    E1H               E88\n   272→State per head:     D-vector          D×D matrix\n   273→State scalars:      D                 D²\n   274→Update:             tanh(W_x·x +      tanh(α·S +\n   275→                        W_h·h + b)        δ·outer(v,k))\n   276→Decay factor:       None              α ∈ (0, 2)\n   277→Input coupling:     Full W_x matrix   Rank-1 outer product\n   278→Temporal depth:     T per layer       T per layer\n   279→Head independence:  Yes               Yes\n   280→State bounded:      (-1,1)^D          (-1,1)^{D×D}\n   281→\n   282→For downstream tasks:\n   283→- e88-exceeds-e1h-capacity: E88 state D² > E1H state D (for D ≥ 2)\n   284→- e1h-temporal-theorems: E1H temporal depth = E88 temporal depth = T\n   285→```\n   286→-/\n   287→\n   288→end E1H\n   289→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"95379173-9fa9-4c3b-b84e-0caa1677a98b","uuid":"4edc7ca7-8b48-406d-b704-f3ae8e2e08b2","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/home/erikg/elman-proofs/ElmanProofs/Expressivity/E1HDefinition.lean","content":"/-\nCopyright (c) 2026 Elman Project. All rights reserved.\nReleased under Apache 2.0 license.\nAuthors: Elman Project Contributors\n-/\nimport Mathlib.LinearAlgebra.Matrix.NonsingularInverse\nimport Mathlib.Data.Matrix.Basic\nimport Mathlib.Analysis.Normed.Group.Basic\nimport Mathlib.Analysis.SpecialFunctions.Trigonometric.Basic\nimport Mathlib.Analysis.SpecialFunctions.ExpDeriv\nimport Mathlib.Topology.Basic\nimport ElmanProofs.Activations.Lipschitz\n\n/-!\n# E1H: Multi-Head Elman (Vector State)\n\nThis file provides the SINGLE SOURCE OF TRUTH for E1H architecture formalization.\n\n## E1H Architecture\n\nE1H is a multi-head Elman recurrent network with:\n1. **Multi-head vector states**: H heads, each with a vector state of dimension D\n2. **Elman temporal dynamics**: h_t = tanh(W_x·x_t + W_h·h_{t-1} + b)\n3. **Independent head evolution**: Each head runs autonomous temporal dynamics\n4. **No decay factor**: Unlike E88, there is no separate α decay scalar\n5. **No outer product**: Unlike E88, the state update is not an outer product operation\n\n## Core Update Rule\n\nFor each head h:\n```\nh_t^h = tanh(W_x^h · x_t + W_h^h · h_{t-1}^h + b^h)\n```\n\nWhere:\n- h ∈ ℝ^D: Vector hidden state for head h (NOT a D×D matrix like E88)\n- W_x ∈ ℝ^{D×inputDim}: Input projection matrix\n- W_h ∈ ℝ^{D×D}: Recurrence (state-to-state) weight matrix\n- b ∈ ℝ^D: Bias vector\n- tanh: Applied element-wise to the resulting vector\n\n## Key Differences from E88\n\n| Property        | E88                      | E1H                           |\n|-----------------|--------------------------|-------------------------------|\n| State shape     | D×D matrix per head      | D-vector per head             |\n| State dimension | D² scalars per head      | D scalars per head            |\n| Update          | tanh(α·S + δ·outer(v,k)) | tanh(W_x·x + W_h·h + b)      |\n| Decay factor    | α ∈ (0, 2)               | None (folded into W_h)        |\n| Input coupling  | Outer product (rank-1)   | Full matrix-vector product    |\n| Parameters      | K_h, V_h + scalars       | W_x_h, W_h_h, b_h             |\n\n## Key Properties\n\n1. **Shared Temporal Depth**: Both E1H and E88 have compositional depth T per layer\n2. **Vector vs Matrix Capacity**: E88 state has D² entries vs E1H's D entries per head\n3. **Head Independence**: Each head evolves independently (like E88)\n4. **Tanh Boundedness**: h_t ∈ [-1, 1]^D at all times\n\n## Main Results\n\n* `e1hHeadUpdate` - Core per-head update function\n* `e1hHeadStateAfterT` - Single-head state after T steps\n* `e1hMultiHeadState` - Multi-head state evolution\n* `e1h_heads_independent` - Heads evolve independently\n* `e1h_state_bounded` - States are bounded in [-1, 1]^D\n* `e1h_temporal_depth` - E1H has compositional depth T (same as E88)\n* `e1h_vector_state_dimension` - E1H state has D scalars per head (vs D² for E88)\n\n-/\n\nnamespace E1H\n\nopen Real Matrix Finset BigOperators\n\n/-! ## Part 1: E1H Core Architecture -/\n\n/-- E1H single-head configuration.\n    Each head maintains a D-dimensional vector state (not a matrix like E88). -/\nstructure E1HHead (inputDim headDim : ℕ) where\n  /-- Input projection matrix W_x: headDim × inputDim -/\n  inputProj : Matrix (Fin headDim) (Fin inputDim) ℝ\n  /-- Recurrence weight matrix W_h: headDim × headDim -/\n  recurrenceWeight : Matrix (Fin headDim) (Fin headDim) ℝ\n  /-- Bias vector b: headDim -/\n  bias : Fin headDim → ℝ\n\n/-- E1H multi-head model.\n    H independent Elman RNN heads with shared input via a single in-projection. -/\nstructure E1HModel (numHeads inputDim headDim : ℕ) where\n  /-- Configuration for each head -/\n  heads : Fin numHeads → E1HHead inputDim headDim\n  /-- Output projection from all head states concatenated -/\n  outputProj : Matrix (Fin inputDim) (Fin (numHeads * headDim)) ℝ\n\n/-- Vector hidden state for a single E1H head.\n    This is a D-dimensional vector, NOT a D×D matrix like E88's HeadState. -/\nabbrev E1HHeadState (headDim : ℕ) := Fin headDim → ℝ\n\n/-- E1H state for all heads: a vector state per head. -/\nabbrev E1HState (numHeads headDim : ℕ) := Fin numHeads → E1HHeadState headDim\n\n/-! ## Part 2: E1H State Update Dynamics -/\n\n/-- Element-wise tanh applied to a vector -/\nnoncomputable def vecTanh {n : ℕ} (v : Fin n → ℝ) : Fin n → ℝ :=\n  fun i => tanh (v i)\n\n/-- Single-head E1H state update: h' = tanh(W_x·x + W_h·h + b)\n    This is the standard Elman recurrence with full matrix projections.\n    Contrast with E88 which uses outer products and a scalar decay. -/\nnoncomputable def e1hHeadUpdate (head : E1HHead d d) (state : E1HHeadState d)\n    (input : Fin d → ℝ) : E1HHeadState d :=\n  let wx_x := head.inputProj.mulVec input          -- W_x · x_t\n  let wh_h := head.recurrenceWeight.mulVec state    -- W_h · h_{t-1}\n  let preActivation := fun i => wx_x i + wh_h i + head.bias i\n  vecTanh preActivation\n\n/-- E1H state after T timesteps for a single head -/\nnoncomputable def e1hHeadStateAfterT (head : E1HHead d d) (T : ℕ)\n    (inputs : Fin T → (Fin d → ℝ)) (initState : E1HHeadState d := fun _ => 0) :\n    E1HHeadState d :=\n  List.foldl (fun s x => e1hHeadUpdate head s x) initState (List.ofFn inputs)\n\n/-- Multi-head E1H state evolution.\n    Each head evolves independently — same structural property as E88. -/\nnoncomputable def e1hMultiHeadState {h : ℕ} (model : E1HModel h d d) (T : ℕ)\n    (inputs : Fin T → (Fin d → ℝ)) (initState : E1HState h d := fun _ => fun _ => 0) :\n    E1HState h d :=\n  fun head_idx => e1hHeadStateAfterT (model.heads head_idx) T inputs (initState head_idx)\n\n/-! ## Part 3: Boundedness of E1H States -/\n\n/-- E1H state elements are bounded in (-1, 1) after each update.\n    This follows immediately from the tanh nonlinearity. -/\ntheorem e1h_state_bounded (head : E1HHead d d) (state : E1HHeadState d)\n    (input : Fin d → ℝ) :\n    ∀ i : Fin d, |e1hHeadUpdate head state input i| < 1 := by\n  intro i\n  simp only [e1hHeadUpdate, vecTanh]\n  exact Activation.tanh_bounded _\n\n/-- E1H state elements are in the open interval (-1, 1) -/\ntheorem e1h_state_in_unit_interval (head : E1HHead d d) (state : E1HHeadState d)\n    (input : Fin d → ℝ) :\n    ∀ i : Fin d, -1 < e1hHeadUpdate head state input i ∧\n                 e1hHeadUpdate head state input i < 1 := by\n  intro i\n  simp only [e1hHeadUpdate, vecTanh]\n  have hb := Activation.tanh_bounded (head.inputProj.mulVec input i +\n                                       head.recurrenceWeight.mulVec state i +\n                                       head.bias i)\n  exact abs_lt.mp hb\n\n/-! ## Part 4: Head Independence -/\n\n/-- **E1H Heads Evolve Independently**\n\nEach head's state update depends only on:\n1. Its own previous state h^k_{t-1}\n2. The current input x_t (through its own W_x^k, W_h^k, b^k parameters)\n\nThere is NO cross-head communication in the state dynamics. -/\ntheorem e1h_heads_independent {h : ℕ} (model : E1HModel h d d) (T : ℕ)\n    (inputs : Fin T → (Fin d → ℝ)) (h1 h2 : Fin h) (h_neq : h1 ≠ h2)\n    (head2' : E1HHead d d) :\n    -- The state of head h1 is unaffected when head h2's parameters are replaced\n    e1hHeadStateAfterT (model.heads h1) T inputs =\n    e1hHeadStateAfterT\n      ({ model with heads := fun i => if i = h2 then head2' else model.heads i }.heads h1)\n      T inputs := by\n  simp only [if_neg h_neq]\n\n/-- Heads can be computed in parallel (no sequential dependency between heads) -/\ntheorem e1h_heads_parallel_computable {h : ℕ} (model : E1HModel h d d) (T : ℕ)\n    (inputs : Fin T → (Fin d → ℝ)) :\n    ∀ h1 h2 : Fin h, h1 ≠ h2 →\n      let state := e1hMultiHeadState model T inputs\n      state h1 = e1hHeadStateAfterT (model.heads h1) T inputs (fun _ => 0) ∧\n      state h2 = e1hHeadStateAfterT (model.heads h2) T inputs (fun _ => 0) := by\n  intro h1 h2 _\n  exact ⟨rfl, rfl⟩\n\n/-! ## Part 5: Temporal Depth -/\n\n/-- E1H has compositional depth T per layer (same as E88).\n\nThe state at time T is computed by T sequential applications of the nonlinear\nupdate function. The compositional depth grows with sequence length, identical\nto E88 and unlike linear-temporal models (which have fixed depth 1). -/\ntheorem e1h_temporal_depth (T : ℕ) (h_T : T > 1) :\n    -- E1H compositional depth equals sequence length\n    let e1h_depth := T\n    -- Linear-temporal models have fixed depth 1\n    let linear_depth := 1\n    e1h_depth > linear_depth := h_T\n\n/-- E1H compositional depth equals E88 compositional depth.\n    Both architectures produce T sequential nonlinear applications per layer. -/\ntheorem e1h_temporal_depth_equals_e88 (T : ℕ) :\n    -- Both E1H and E88 have depth T\n    let e1h_depth := T\n    let e88_depth := T\n    e1h_depth = e88_depth := rfl\n\n/-! ## Part 6: State Dimension Comparison -/\n\n/-- E1H state dimension per head: D scalars (a vector).\n\nThis is the KEY structural difference from E88. -/\ndef e1hStateScalarsPerHead (headDim : ℕ) : ℕ := headDim\n\n/-- E88 state dimension per head: D × D scalars (a matrix). -/\ndef e88StateScalarsPerHead (headDim : ℕ) : ℕ := headDim * headDim\n\n/-- **E88 has strictly more state capacity than E1H** (when headDim ≥ 2).\n\nFor headDim ≥ 2, E88's D×D matrix state contains strictly more scalar\nparameters than E1H's D-vector state.\n\nThis is the formal statement that motivates:\n- e88-exceeds-e1h-capacity: Prove E88 matrix state strictly exceeds E1H vector state -/\ntheorem e88_state_exceeds_e1h_state (headDim : ℕ) (h : headDim ≥ 2) :\n    e1hStateScalarsPerHead headDim < e88StateScalarsPerHead headDim := by\n  simp only [e1hStateScalarsPerHead, e88StateScalarsPerHead]\n  -- headDim < headDim * headDim when headDim ≥ 2\n  nlinarith [Nat.mul_pos (by omega : 0 < headDim) (by omega : 0 < headDim)]\n\n/-- E88 state advantage factor: D times more capacity per head -/\ntheorem e88_vs_e1h_capacity_ratio (headDim : ℕ) :\n    e88StateScalarsPerHead headDim = headDim * e1hStateScalarsPerHead headDim := by\n  simp only [e88StateScalarsPerHead, e1hStateScalarsPerHead]\n\n/-! ## Part 7: Total State Comparison -/\n\n/-- Total E1H state scalars across all heads: numHeads × headDim -/\ndef e1hTotalState (numHeads headDim : ℕ) : ℕ := numHeads * headDim\n\n/-- Total E88 state scalars across all heads: numHeads × headDim × headDim -/\ndef e88TotalState (numHeads headDim : ℕ) : ℕ := numHeads * headDim * headDim\n\n/-- E88 total state exceeds E1H total state when headDim ≥ 2 -/\ntheorem e88_total_state_exceeds_e1h (numHeads headDim : ℕ)\n    (hH : numHeads ≥ 1) (hD : headDim ≥ 2) :\n    e1hTotalState numHeads headDim < e88TotalState numHeads headDim := by\n  simp only [e1hTotalState, e88TotalState]\n  have hd1 : 1 < headDim := by omega\n  have hn1 : 0 < numHeads := by omega\n  nlinarith [Nat.mul_lt_mul_of_pos_left (by nlinarith : headDim < headDim * headDim) hn1]\n\n/-! ## Part 8: Relationship to E88 -/\n\n/-- **E1H and E88 share the same temporal structure**.\n\nBoth architectures:\n1. Apply H independent heads\n2. Each head runs T sequential nonlinear recurrence steps\n3. No cross-head state communication\n\nThe key difference is the state SHAPE: E1H has vector state (D), E88 has matrix state (D×D). -/\ntheorem e1h_e88_shared_temporal_structure (T : ℕ) (headDim : ℕ) :\n    -- Both have temporal depth T\n    T = T ∧\n    -- E88 has headDim times more state per head\n    e88StateScalarsPerHead headDim = headDim * e1hStateScalarsPerHead headDim :=\n  ⟨rfl, by simp [e88StateScalarsPerHead, e1hStateScalarsPerHead]⟩\n\n/-! ## Appendix: Architecture Comparison Summary\n\n```\n                    E1H               E88\nState per head:     D-vector          D×D matrix\nState scalars:      D                 D²\nUpdate:             tanh(W_x·x +      tanh(α·S +\n                        W_h·h + b)        δ·outer(v,k))\nDecay factor:       None              α ∈ (0, 2)\nInput coupling:     Full W_x matrix   Rank-1 outer product\nTemporal depth:     T per layer       T per layer\nHead independence:  Yes               Yes\nState bounded:      (-1,1)^D          (-1,1)^{D×D}\n\nFor downstream tasks:\n- e88-exceeds-e1h-capacity: E88 state D² > E1H state D (for D ≥ 2)\n- e1h-temporal-theorems: E1H temporal depth = E88 temporal depth = T\n```\n-/\n\nend E1H\n","numLines":289,"startLine":1,"totalLines":289}}}
