sable retrieval that E1H can't achieve. Now I'm structuring the formal theorem to capture these three-level distinctions.\n\nWriting the hierarchy theorem... I'm establishing the key theoretical results that support each part of the argument—showing that linear systems fundamentally can't compute thresholds, that E1H heads can achieve threshold-like behavior through saturation, that E88 enables content-based addressing while E1H doesn't, and that E88's state capacity scales quadratically compared to E1H's linear scaling.\n\nNow I need to formalize this hierarchy properly in Lean. The task asks me to prove that LinearSSM ⊊ E1H ⊊ E88, which means defining what it means for one architecture to be strictly contained within another. Rather than trying to define formal \"computable\" predicates for each, I'll use the witness-based approach with the specific counterexamples I've already identified.\n\nWriting the Lean formalization... I'm proving that linear SSMs can't compute threshold functions by applying the linear limitations result, then showing E1H can achieve this capability through its recurrence weights and tanh saturation. Next I need to establish the E1H ⊊ E88 separation using content-addressable matrix retrieval as the witness function. I'm now establishing the full expressivity hierarchy, starting with the strict separation between linear SSMs and E1H—specifically that linear models can't compute threshold functions while E1H can operate in saturation regimes with specific recurrence weight constraints. Completing the proof structure with the capacity separation theorem... The namespace resolution checks out—since `E1HTemporalTheorems` opens the `E1H` namespace, `E1HHead` in the theorem statement correctly resolves to `E1H.E1HHead`, so the types match between the hierarchy requirement and my theorem definition.\n\nFor the capacity separation, the `e88_addressable_e1h_not` theorem already captures the key insight: E88 has D² parameters while E1H only has D, wh