{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01AYT2tauM3Nrv2Z52GiU6bL","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→/-\n     2→Copyright (c) 2026 Elman Project. All rights reserved.\n     3→Released under Apache 2.0 license.\n     4→Authors: Elman Project Contributors\n     5→-/\n     6→import Mathlib.LinearAlgebra.Matrix.NonsingularInverse\n     7→import Mathlib.Data.Matrix.Basic\n     8→import Mathlib.Analysis.Normed.Group.Basic\n     9→import Mathlib.Topology.Basic\n    10→import ElmanProofs.Expressivity.LinearLimitations\n    11→import ElmanProofs.Expressivity.LinearCapacity\n    12→import ElmanProofs.Expressivity.MultiLayerLimitations\n    13→\n    14→/-!\n    15→# Running Parity Impossibility for Linear-Temporal Models\n    16→\n    17→This file proves that running parity cannot be computed by linear-temporal models,\n    18→regardless of depth. This extends the XOR impossibility proof to arbitrary-length\n    19→sequences.\n    20→\n    21→## Main Results\n    22→\n    23→* `parity_T_not_affine`: Parity of T binary inputs is not an affine function (for T ≥ 2)\n    24→* `linear_cannot_running_parity`: Linear RNNs cannot compute running parity\n    25→* `multilayer_linear_cannot_parity`: D-layer linear-temporal models cannot compute parity\n    26→\n    27→## Key Insight\n    28→\n    29→Running parity requires computing `x_1 ⊕ x_2 ⊕ ... ⊕ x_t` at each position t.\n    30→Since XOR is not a linear function, and linear temporal aggregation can only\n    31→produce linear combinations, running parity is impossible for any model where\n    32→temporal dynamics are linear (including Mamba2, MinGRU, MinLSTM).\n    33→\n    34→## Connection to Existing Proofs\n    35→\n    36→This file builds on LinearLimitations.lean which proves:\n    37→- `xor_not_affine`: XOR on 2 bits is not affine\n    38→- `linear_cannot_xor`: Linear RNNs cannot compute XOR\n    39→\n    40→We extend these results to arbitrary-length running parity.\n    41→-/\n    42→\n    43→namespace Expressivity\n    44→\n    45→open Matrix Finset BigOperators\n    46→\n    47→variable {n m k : ℕ}\n    48→\n    49→/-! ## Running Parity Definition -/\n    50→\n    51→/-- Parity indicator function: returns 1 if sum is odd, 0 if even.\n    52→    For integer sums s, we have: s is odd iff s - 2*floor(s/2) = 1 -/\n    53→noncomputable def parityIndicator (s : ℝ) : ℝ :=\n    54→  if s - 2 * ⌊s / 2⌋ = 1 then 1 else 0\n    55→\n    56→/-- Running parity function: at each position t, output parity of inputs 0..t.\n    57→    For binary inputs, parity = 1 iff sum is odd. -/\n    58→noncomputable def runningParity (T : ℕ) : (Fin T → (Fin 1 → ℝ)) → (Fin T → (Fin 1 → ℝ)) :=\n    59→  fun inputs t => fun _ =>\n    60→    let prefix_sum := ∑ s : Fin T, if s.val ≤ t.val then inputs s 0 else 0\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"95379173-9fa9-4c3b-b84e-0caa1677a98b","uuid":"c5155e37-b130-428d-bc7a-846419eb54d3","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/home/erikg/elman-proofs/ElmanProofs/Expressivity/RunningParity.lean","content":"/-\nCopyright (c) 2026 Elman Project. All rights reserved.\nReleased under Apache 2.0 license.\nAuthors: Elman Project Contributors\n-/\nimport Mathlib.LinearAlgebra.Matrix.NonsingularInverse\nimport Mathlib.Data.Matrix.Basic\nimport Mathlib.Analysis.Normed.Group.Basic\nimport Mathlib.Topology.Basic\nimport ElmanProofs.Expressivity.LinearLimitations\nimport ElmanProofs.Expressivity.LinearCapacity\nimport ElmanProofs.Expressivity.MultiLayerLimitations\n\n/-!\n# Running Parity Impossibility for Linear-Temporal Models\n\nThis file proves that running parity cannot be computed by linear-temporal models,\nregardless of depth. This extends the XOR impossibility proof to arbitrary-length\nsequences.\n\n## Main Results\n\n* `parity_T_not_affine`: Parity of T binary inputs is not an affine function (for T ≥ 2)\n* `linear_cannot_running_parity`: Linear RNNs cannot compute running parity\n* `multilayer_linear_cannot_parity`: D-layer linear-temporal models cannot compute parity\n\n## Key Insight\n\nRunning parity requires computing `x_1 ⊕ x_2 ⊕ ... ⊕ x_t` at each position t.\nSince XOR is not a linear function, and linear temporal aggregation can only\nproduce linear combinations, running parity is impossible for any model where\ntemporal dynamics are linear (including Mamba2, MinGRU, MinLSTM).\n\n## Connection to Existing Proofs\n\nThis file builds on LinearLimitations.lean which proves:\n- `xor_not_affine`: XOR on 2 bits is not affine\n- `linear_cannot_xor`: Linear RNNs cannot compute XOR\n\nWe extend these results to arbitrary-length running parity.\n-/\n\nnamespace Expressivity\n\nopen Matrix Finset BigOperators\n\nvariable {n m k : ℕ}\n\n/-! ## Running Parity Definition -/\n\n/-- Parity indicator function: returns 1 if sum is odd, 0 if even.\n    For integer sums s, we have: s is odd iff s - 2*floor(s/2) = 1 -/\nnoncomputable def parityIndicator (s : ℝ) : ℝ :=\n  if s - 2 * ⌊s / 2⌋ = 1 then 1 else 0\n\n/-- Running parity function: at each position t, output parity of inputs 0..t.\n    For binary inputs, parity = 1 iff sum is odd. -/\nnoncomputable def runningParity (T : ℕ) : (Fin T → (Fin 1 → ℝ)) → (Fin T → (Fin 1 → ℝ)) :=\n  fun inputs t => fun _ =>\n    let prefix_sum := ∑ s : Fin T, if s.val ≤ t.val then inputs s 0 else 0","numLines":60,"startLine":1,"totalLines":342}}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01DqbprqbueDsxFvn5pXYeWp","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Good. Now I have enough context to write the hierarchy file. Let me write a clean Lean file that:\n\n1. Defines expressivity classes for each architecture\n2. Proves strict containments using existing theorems\n\nThe key insight for the formal hierarchy is:\n\n**Linear SSM ⊊ E1H**: \n- Witness: XOR function (or threshold function)\n- `¬ LinearlyComputable (xorReal on binary)` via `linear_cannot_xor`\n- For E1H CAN compute XOR: This requires defining what E1H computation means formally\n\nActually, rather than trying to prove \"E1H CAN compute threshold function exactly\", let me use the approach of showing:\n\n\n- E1H has strictly more compositional depth than linear SSMs (T steps vs 1 step effective)\n- E1H is nonlinear while linear SSMs are linear\n- Use the existing `linear_cannot_threshold` and `e1h_can_threshold` (the latter just shows parameters exist)\n\nFor the formal hierarchy, I'll define a separation based on what each architecture type can represent, and use the existing proofs as the separation witnesses. I'll leverage the fact that linear SSM outputs are linear in inputs while E1H can express nonlinear functions through its compositional structure.\n\nThe hierarchy would show E88 has a D² dimensional state per head versus E1H's D, and I could formalize this by demonstrating E1H can approximate functions like XOR that linear systems cannot compute, though that requires additional work to establish the approximation bounds precisely.\n\nLooking at the actual task structure, I need to verify three things: that linear SSMs can't compute parity (already proven in existing work), that E1H can compute parity and threshold functions (the parity proof has a gap but the threshold proof is complete), and that E88 can store quadratic state information E1H structurally cannot access.\n\nThe key insight is that E1H operates in a saturation regime with specific parameter bounds that enable nonlinear threshold behavior, whereas linear SSMs are fundamentally constrained to linear combinations. Now I'm formalizing the hierarchy theorem that captures these three separations.\n\nWriting the formal hierarchy proof... Continuing with the formal proof structure, establishing that E88 has strictly greater state capacity than E1H for dimensions ≥ 2, and that E88 can perform content-addressable matrix retrieval operations that E1H's vector-based state cannot support. I'm checking the function signature for `linear_cannot_xor` more carefully—it takes inputs of type `Fin 2 → (Fin 1 → ℝ)` and returns `Fin 1 → ℝ`, so my lambda argument needs to align with that structure rather than what I initially wrote. Still writing the theorem... I'm realizing the distinction between the theorem statement itself and its proof—`e1h_can_threshold` is the proof term, not the proposition, so I need to reference the actual statement type to use it in a conjunction. theorem gives us `e1h_can_threshold : (the_proposition)` as a proof term. If I want to use the proposition in my conjunction, I need to write out the proposition type explicitly.\n\nSo I need to structure the hierarchy theorem with explicit proposition types, then prove each component using the corresponding proof terms. For the full hierarchy, I'd construct a tuple of proofs where each element corresponds to one of the propositions in the conjunction.\n\nFor `e1h_can_threshold` specifically, the proposition type is an existential statement about an E1HHead and a threshold value θ with certain constraints on their properties. Since the namespace handling means `E1HHead` refers to the same type whether qualified or not, I can use the proof term directly as long as the proposition types match exactly.\n\nMy approach is to construct the conjunction by referencing the existing theorem statements and using `exact` to discharge each goal, being careful about namespace resolution.\n\nWriting the Lean proof structure... Writing Lean 4 proof file...","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1879,"cache_read_input_tokens":73628,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1879},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"95379173-9fa9-4c3b-b84e-0caa1677a98b","uuid":"39fd521c-8b6b-4331-afb1-11ba55b888e5"}
